or</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A2. Motivation and Objectives (Items 5, 6):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=reviewerQualification\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>2.&nbsp;Poor</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A3. Technical Overview (Item 7):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=potential\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>2.&nbsp;Poor</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A4. Activities and Roles (Items 8-10):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=fixability\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A5. Impact on Curricula (Item 11):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=novelty\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>2.&nbsp;Poor</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A6. Team (Items 12.1 and 12.2):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=technicalMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A7. Mentors (Item 13):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=interestToCommunity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A8. Outreach (Items 14, 16, 17):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=longevity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A9. Please provide your comments and suggestions for improvement on Items A1-A8 in 8 succeeding paragraphs, numbered paragraphs.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>1. The clinical aspect of the work outlined is rather weak. It does not gel with the focus on amyloid proteins. There could be many reasons for relapse of the disease in patients with nephrotic syndrome and treated with steroids and/or immunosuppressives. Trying to identify proteins in urine and sera samples of the patients, without any scientific rationale, is not likely to be fruitful. Moreover, there are already work in this regard, which have not been quoted. There is also much data available on kidney biopsies, another commitment of the proposal. These are not going to add on something new to the focus area of HuSim. 2. Section 5 - This section is very poorly written. There are no references given for the write up on &#39;status of knowledge&#39;. There is no clarity on &#39;unmet challenges&#39;. Section 6 - Objectives are not clearly written -they need to be specific. The first 2 paragraphs seem redundant and not linked to the proposal&#39;s focus. For eg,synucleins are localised in pre-synaptic nerve terminals in brain and p53 is a tumor suppressor protein (refer page 12 of the proposal). What are their relevance to nephrotic syndrome disease? 3. Section 7.1 has started with objective 3 rather objectives 1 &amp; 2!. The second paragraph refers to the important role of synuclein protein in Parkinson&#39;s disease. This proposal however addresses nephrotic syndrome rather than Parkinson&#39;s disease. No specific mention of what additions would be made to scientific and / or technological advancements. Section 7.2 - It is not clear how the data acquired on nephrotic syndrome patients will be linked to amyloid proteins. There is no clarity in the write up. For example, NIPER would be studying synuclein (found in brain) and p53 (tumor marker). These would be of no direct relevance to the study proposed by AIIMS, which will acquire clinical data from patients with nephrotic syndrome. The other proposed work in AIIMS on proteomics and metabolomics from patient serum and urine are areas where there are reports available in the literature. These studies are likely to give non-specific information. There seem to be a disconnect between the work in NIPER and AIIMS. Section 7.3 - The computatioal methods are already developed by the team members. It is not clear what is the novelty in the proposal. 4. Section 8 - Again not well written. There is no mention of the objectives while elaborating on the tasks. The task by AIIMS mentions only proteomics work and not metabolomics (mentioned in page 15) Section 9 - New partner S.A.S. Nagar is introduced. It is not mentioned in the PIN list!. Mention is made of only objectives 1 and 2. No mention of objectives 2 and 4!. Section 10 - Objective 2 (AIIMS): It is not clear whether proteomic or metabolomic studies will be performed on the serum and urine samples. It is mentioned that proteomic studies will be carried out at Dept. of Biophysics, AIIMS but no mention is made of the metabolomic studies. The investigators have mentioned that atleast 175 MS spectra will be made available for machine learning. There is no clarity on what samples will be used for these spectra nad how will they be compared with the proteomics data. No technical clarity on how the proteomics data would be generated. Studying six samples each from healthy controls and patients with nephrotic syndrome seem too little. 5. Section 11A not filled! Section 11B - If the basic softwares are already developed by the team, why are 2 students required?. There is also a mismatch with the number of students requested in the budget section. It is 3 there and two in this section (11B). 6. Section 12.1 - There seems to be no areas of interaction between AIIMS &amp; NIPER and IIT Delhi and NIPER!. The only interaction mentioned is that between IIT Delhi and AIIMS 8. Improving utility of machine learning in mass spectrometric data analysis is not the focus of the HuSim program.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B1. Any major mismatches in the proposed line item costs with the proposed item/work, in the format: Budget-head-Institution: Remarks. Example: &lt;Manpower-IITX: Remarks&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>IIT Delhi (i) Summary sheet mentions Rs.186.39 lakhs whereas the budget breakup mentions Rs. 198.70 lakhs. What is the actual budget?. (ii) IIT Delhi has only committed for machine learning but not for any data acquisition. However, under the equipment head, they have asked for a 2D Gel Electrophoresis worth 50 lakhs! (iii)Only 2 PhD students have been requested in the proposal. However, the budget is given for 3 PhD students. There seems to be no developmental work committed by IIT Delhi. In their own words, they will only input the data obtained from AIIMS or NIPER into the machine learning programme already developed by them. What is then the need for 3 PhD students, when there is no developmental work? NIPER The equipment requested for, i.e. &#39;Biosafety cabinet&#39; should be there in their lab. AIIMS The budget section is very casually written. For example, (i) it is not clear what software upgradation is required. No details are given. (ii) The total budget required for manpower is not mentioned. It is not clear whether the requirement is 5 personnel or only 2 RAs. (iii)No justification provided for any budget heads.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B2. Any major equipment proposed for purchase that may be otherwise possible to share with others or is usable through outsourcing, without adversely affecting the work.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>2D Gel Electrophoresis by IIT Delhi Biosafety cabinet should be available in a lab which has ongoing projects(refer cv of Dr. Ipsita Roy)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C1. Any Additional Comments:</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>There are 22 references listed in the reference section. However, only 12 are mentioned in the text. Looks like an incomplete &#39;cut and paste&#39; from somewhere. CVs of LINs and PINs are missing!. Only 3 of the 7 are provided. Of them, only Dr. Jayadeva has provided details of his ongoing projects. Dr. Bhowmick has not provided any information on his completed or ongoing projects. Dr. Ipsita Roy has only mentioned titles of the projects. No other details are provided. CVs of all the mentors have also not been provided. There is no clarity on the final &#39;easy to use program function for clinicians&#39;. The investigators have not declared anywhere the overlap/relationships with their past or ongoing work</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C2. Your Overall Evaluation:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp