>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A3. Technical Overview (Item 7):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=potential\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>2.&nbsp;Poor</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A4. Activities and Roles (Items 8-10):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=fixability\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>2.&nbsp;Poor</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A5. Impact on Curricula (Item 11):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=novelty\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A6. Team (Items 12.1 and 12.2):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=technicalMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>2.&nbsp;Poor</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A7. Mentors (Item 13):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=interestToCommunity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A8. Outreach (Items 14, 16, 17):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=longevity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>2.&nbsp;Poor</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>B1. Any major mismatches in the proposed line item costs with the proposed item/work, in the format: Budget-head-Institution: Remarks. Example: &lt;Manpower-IITX: Remarks&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>No</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B2. Any major equipment proposed for purchase that may be otherwise possible to share with others or is usable through outsourcing, without adversely affecting the work.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>NA</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B3. If any proposed major equipment is costing more than Rs. 2,50,000, and sharing/outsourcing is possible but not suggested in the proposal, then (i) do you know if that equipment is already available (particularly in India) where its sharing/outsourcing may be possible, and (ii) is it absolutely necessary for the project.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>NA</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C2. Your Overall Evaluation:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=grammar\">(?)</a>(shown only to chairs)</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>C.&nbsp;Not Recommended for Support</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#008000\"><strong>Reviewer 5 :</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A1. Problem (Item 4):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=overAllMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A2. Motivation and Objectives (Items 5, 6):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=reviewerQualification\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A3. Technical Overview (Item 7):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=potential\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A4. Activities and Roles (Items 8-10):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=fixability\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A5. Impact on Curricula (Item 11):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=novelty\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A6. Team (Items 12.1 and 12.2):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=technicalMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A7. Mentors (Item 13):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=interestToCommunity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A8. Outreach (Items 14, 16, 17):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=longevity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A9. Please provide your comments and suggestions for improvement on Items A1-A8 in 8 succeeding paragraphs, numbered paragraphs.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>1. AD is not a disease that has a major impact in India. According to the statistics (quoted by the investigators), 4 million Indians over the age of 60 are affected. It is pertinent to note that some of the changes observed in MRI in AD patients are also seen in elderly individuals with normal cognition. So, some of the changes in brain are age related and not disease specific. Item 4, end 1st paragraph - It is not clear how coming up with a multi-modal holistic approach can act as a biomarker for accurate diagnosis!. 2. Item 5- The statement that brain signals can be measured at microscopic level using MRI is totally wrong. The investigators hypothesize to use fMRI, DTI (MRI), EEG and clinical data to find out the precise solution to this problem!. This cannot be called a scientific hypothesis. It is only using the available technology to study the problem. So, this project has no hypothesis to base its studies. It is not clear whether the investigators are aware of the fact fMRI and other neuroimaging data repositories are available in public domain for AD. For example, ADNI 1 &amp; 2 (ADNI - Alzheimer&#39;s Disease Neuroimaging Initiative). There is lot of data on the possible positive role of fMRI and DTI in AD patients. This group&#39;s work will be a repeat and generate more data but nothing new to add. There is already huge amount of information on the various markers for AD from biochemical, structural, functional to cognitive. This project has to contribute something new and not add more of the same data to what is already available in the literature. The objectives straddle vast areas and do not appear practically feasible. 3.Development of cognitive battery does not gel with the other objectives. It should be dropped. The investigators have not given any information on their past and other ongoing work. 4. Cognitive battery development for behavioural assessment of progression of pathology - there are many underlying causes for behavioural changes including side effects of medication. So, cognitive assessment cannot isolate the effects due to pathology. There will also be age related changes, which again will vary from person o person. So, it is not clear how cognitive battery development will be useful in diagnosis, treatment and prognosis as the investigators claim. Technical plan Item 10 - It is not clear why this section has introduction to topics and concepts, especially in the section on cognitive battery but no methodology for the study. Developing methods for image processing and analysis of fMRI and DTI data - there are readily available methods and protocols for these analysis. No technical plan for a new methodology has been outlined. In what way the proposed development by this group will be different and superior to the existing analysis softwares. There is again a description of the usefulness of fMRI and DTI but no technical and experimental details on how they are going to be carried out. At what field strength will the MR studies be carried out?. Will they use other than EPI (Echo Planar Imaging) for their MR studies?. If so, what are those sequences and parameters?. What are the tasks to be designed for the fMRI studies?. The technical plan is completely silent on all these. It is far fetched to correlate behavioural data with structural imaging data.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B1. Any major mismatches in the proposed line item costs with the proposed item/work, in the format: Budget-head-Institution: Remarks. Example: &lt;Manpower-IITX: Remarks&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>None of the investigators have provided justification for any of the budget requirements!. The investigators have mentioned that the project is for 5 years. The budget, however, is give only for 3 years! IIT Delhi is going to do mainly data analysis. Why do they then need 5 PhD students?. They have also asked for high end servers and softwares worth Rs. 30 lakhs. They have not mentioned the facilities already available in the Institute for such work. IIT Mumbai- The budget calculation is wrong. Has to be checked. The overhead for the first year is more than the budget! NBRC has asked for equipments but no details provided. It is not clear what &#39;2&#39; means!. Does it indicate 2 equipments or 2 lakhs? When the investigators are asking for Rs. 350 lakhs, it is imperative they provide sufficient and correct information.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C1. Any Additional Comments:</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Why is the same investigator from NBRC (Dr. Roy) mentioned as PIN1b and PIN2b? Pages are not numbered The page limit has been overshot PI LIN1 (Dr, Shantanu) has provided no information of his past and ongoing projects.. The same is true of Dr. Anubha Gupta from IIIT Delhi. CV of PIN 2a from IIT Mumbai is completely missing. If these investigators do not have time to provide the required information to a project proposal,this reviewer is wondering how will they contribute to the project if funded?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C2. Your Overall Evaluation:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=grammar\">(?)</a>(shown only to chairs)</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>B.&nbsp;Borderline</p>\r\n', '', '1');
INSERT INTO `husmin_old_reviews` (`id`, `priject_title`, `reviewdata`, `by_whome`, `review_count`) VALUES
(18, 'project485', '<h4><span style=\"color:#008000\"><strong>Reviewer 1 :</strong></span></h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A1. Problem (Item 4):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=overAllMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>6.&nbsp;Please check comments given below</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A2. Motivation and Objectives (Items 5, 6):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=reviewerQualification\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>6.&nbsp;Please check comments given below</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A3. Technical Overview (Item 7):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=potential\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>6.&nbsp;Please check comments given below</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A4. Activities and Roles (Items 8-10):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=fixability\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>6.&nbsp;Please check comments given below</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A5. Impact on Curricula (Item 11):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=novelty\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>6.&nbsp;Please check comments given below</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A6. Team (Items 12.1 and 12.2):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=technicalMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>6.&nbsp;Please check comments given below</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A7. Mentors (Item 13):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=interestToCommunity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>6.&nbsp;Please check comments given below</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A8. Outreach (Items 14, 16, 17):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=longevity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>6.&nbsp;Please check comments given below</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A9. Please provide your comments and suggestions for improvement on Items A1-A8 in 8 succeeding paragraphs, numbered paragraphs.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>This is an inter-institutional collaborative project by four scientists. The investigators aim addressing and understanding fundamental cellular and molecular basis/mechanism of Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease (AD). The investigators argue that on one hand it is difficult to extend such study in vivo or in biological samples, and on the other hand it is relatively convenient to study them in silico by mathematical modeling; therefore, they would adopt the latter. To achieve their goals, particularly in relation to AD, they would model hippocampal neurons in silico&nbsp;based on data/information available in the literature and/or in the public domain. They plan achieving their goals by using high power computing, 3D synaptic modeling, genetic manipulation using bioinformatics approach on available data. They also plan to study the role of calcium channels, calcium overloading, role of different channels and ions, etc on model neuronal functioning and then to extrapolate their findings to understand the AD in models in silico. The investigators also have a radiologist in their team to carry out fMRI in humans as well. As an outcome the investigators expect to develop &hellip;&hellip;.. High performance computing facility, new data analysis tools using bioinformatics approach, construct comprehensive neural networks using genes and biomarkers mapped in their respective pathways, etc. My Comments : The investigators have had good training in modeling in reputed established labs abroad and have good publication records. In recognition they have been appointed in &ldquo;class apart&rdquo; Institution of National Importance of this country and they have secured prestigious Wellcome Trust grants. Although it is not too late yet, as there is no preliminary data it appears that they are still in the process of establishing their labs and publication credentials as independent researchers, which I understand takes time. In my opinion the project at present is too ambitious because of the following reasons : i) There is no pilot data to support their claims. There is no mention of difficulties they may face and how would they tackle them, if at all. ii) It is not clear from this write up, what is/are the facility available with the investigators at present. Certainly the investigators have delivered in established labs but it is not the same to develop lab and then deliver. If this project is primarily for developing lab infrastructure, which if at all, then it should have been spelt out accordingly. Further, in that case, the funding agency has to take a call whether to fund such fund intensive project for such infrastructure development. iii) To me scientifically more serious question is, can one extrapolate such in vitro, in silico data/findings (as and when they would have) to predict/extrapolate etiology of complex disease such as AD, particularly without support from wet lab and in vivo data. I would be particularly interested to know the investigators experience and thought in those directions. It is also pertinent to know if the investigators (with or without support from collaborators) have attempted to fit in their earlier in silico/in vitro data/findings in vivo or vice versa. iv) The PIs would depend on data from published papers and/or data available in the public domain. Based on my personal experience, I think, it is prudent having a collaborator experienced in vivo studies/data or to validate in vivo the in silico derived data. It may be spelt out if the mentor would do the job. In this regard I could not understand the role of formal mentor(s); also, I do not understand the necessity of foreign Mentors. What would be the case if the PIs would like to get help from another person/scientist? Don&rsquo;t the PIs have confidence of developing one&rsquo;s own problem and establish themselves as world leaders eventually in years to come? I think, they should be allowed to establish themselves with their ideas unbiased; seniors may offer their help to establish these freshers. However, if the latter need, they can approach who so ever they want and for that they would find ways as like others do. In my opinion, by this they would establish their identity. v) The PIs have mentioned that they possess expertise to carry out such work. However, to be critical, which I am expected to be, there should be some evidence of their track record in terms of deliverability after establishing a lab (i.e. as corresponding authors, etc) that too under our condition. The PIs have not provided any preliminary data to substantiate their claims and/or for a reader like me to depend on their potential as to what has happened with the inputs they have received past years as a reflection of their ability of delivering. vi) The literature survey has been done reasonably well. It appears that they have seamlessly and conveniently used data/publication from modeling studies and that from in vivo data interchangeably to support their view(s) without explicitly clarifying if they differentiated between them. This is glaring because they have not commented on any failures or how to tackle hurdles, which should have been a significant component of a project of this nature. vii) In continuation of above, it appears that the PIs together have received extramural funding to the tune of at least Rs. 9 plus crores (in addition to intramural funding). I admit that nobody (certainly not me) has seen the future, but to extrapolate I would be happy to see reasonable output from such studies before granting heavy investment and such ambitious project like this. viii) Have the PIs exploited the facility already created by such intense funding already received? ix) I also wonder that this project has been based on studies where the PIs have hardly any paper from their past study/work to cite to substantiate or to take their studies forward. By no means I want them to copy and extend their post-doc work only, and in the same spirit it should not be that one should propose seemingly different projects just like that without going deeper into ones being continued. x) Besides, it is amazing that the PIs would establish labs of high calibre, train students, teach students at various levels, carry out workshops, training, etc, etc and then deliver quality output and solve complex problem like AD and that too without any validation. I think, one should have been more realistic. I suggest that the PIs should concentrate in teaching and research to establish themselves as world leaders in coming years and the rest training, workshop etc they can take up thereafter. xi) I do not see any proposal how would the data/findings be validated in vivo. The findings of the PIs need to be validated at least in slice preparation if not in vivo at least in animals. There are enough expertise in the country to do so with whom the PIs may collaborate. In the same breadth, I could not appreciate the academic necessity of the radiologist and his role. Further, I am not sure about the nature of the hospital where the radiologist is associated with; would not someone from a Medical College be better? By the way, is the radiologist PI from a Govt Hospital, of course, the funding agency has to check that. xii) I am not optimistic on the PIs statement on P26, Point 20 under the heading ..&hellip;What are the expectend outcomes of the project? Give only the most important five.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C1. Any Additional Comments:</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>An understanding of the synaptic and network mechanisms that lead to a disruption of episodic memory and spatial map&rsquo; s in AD. A thorough understanding of the molecular mechanisms and gene networks may reveal potential genes whose expression levels may be key indicators associated of the progression and early diagnosis of the disease. A diagnostic tool using fMRI that can act as an early marker of AD. In my opinion, for the PIs to have their claims as above, they need validation in vivo (which I have raised above as well) it may be life time&rsquo;s work. Finally, I suggest, that the PIs need to be more practical. They should try exploiting the facility already created (probably) and build/add/extend on them to build infrastructure to achieve their larger scientific goal(s). While doing so, there must be stress on validation of their data/findings in vivo. They may engage themselves in imparting Training/Workshop, etc once they have established themselves as independent and leaders and do not think they need mentors to steer their work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C2. Your Overall Evaluation:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=grammar\">(?)</a>(shown only to chairs)</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>C.&nbsp;Not Recommended for Support</p>\r\n\r\n<h4><span style=\"color:#008000\"><strong>Reviewer 2&nbsp;:</strong></span></h4>\r\n\r\n<p>A1. Problem (Item 4):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=overAllMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A2. Motivation and Objectives (Items 5, 6):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=reviewerQualification\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A3. Technical Overview (Item 7):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=potential\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A4. Activities and Roles (Items 8-10):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=fixability\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A5. Impact on Curricula (Item 11):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=novelty\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A6. Team (Items 12.1 and 12.2):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=technicalMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A7. Mentors (Item 13):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=interestToCommunity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>5.&nbsp;Excellent</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A8. Outreach (Items 14, 16, 17):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=longevity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A9. Please provide your comments and suggestions for improvement on Items A1-A8 in 8 succeeding paragraphs, numbered paragraphs.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>1.No mention is made of stakeholders. Since this is more of a basic science project, I assume that the beneficiaries (stakeholders?) are the LINs and PINs, in addition to the AD patients, and clinicians, when the promised fMRI diagnostic tool becomes available. 2.The challenges are clearly described as two primary scientific questions, which will drive the proposed efforts to identify aberrant oscillations, their models, mechanisms and signaling pathways. The elucidation of the latter could lead to a noninvasive fMRI test to detect the disruption of these oscillations. These goals are ambitious, but the first stages of modeling, stochastic simulation and discovery of oscillation mechanisms appear to be feasible. 3.The novelty (and the bold conjecture) is that the key to early AD detection lies in brain oscillations, their signaling pathways and observable characteristic signatures. The proposed model validation is statistical and based on mining existing databases for AD pathways, and not on clinical validation. Impact of the results on practice is still a little distant and will depend on validity of the conjecture. 4.Research activities are well distributed across the team in accordance with specialization of its members. The modeling and simulation tools that result from this project will probably have their impact limited to academic and research settings, although an fMRI diagnostic tool based on them is also promised. The proposal says &quot;The fMRI diagnostic tool may be available at the end of three years. Data analysis tools developed to analyse pathways and fMRI images will be continuously made available to external users over three years. Observation: The team is quite small for the volume of work and looking for additional partners may be useful. 5. Introduction of neuroimaging techniques into the Quantitative Biology and Neuroscience curricula is mentioned. Six PhDs (two per PI) are expected to be produced. 6.Team members have ample experience in the area of the proposal as shown by their CVs and located in institutions with adequate infrastructure. No mention is made of the time commitment of the researchers involved. 7. The mentors are well chosen and their role in the project clearly defined, with visits in both directions. 8.Dissemination is planned through two week long workshops in the second and third years. No mention is made of translation of technologies. Suggestion: The proposers will use fMRI machines and virtual reality goggles from vendors -- involving them in this research as partners may be crucial to dissemination of this research outside academia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B1. Any major mismatches in the proposed line item costs with the proposed item/work, in the format: Budget-head-Institution: Remarks. Example: &lt;Manpower-IITX: Remarks&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>None observed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B2. Any major equipment proposed for purchase that may be otherwise possible to share with others or is usable through outsourcing, without adversely affecting the work.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Both PIs in the same institution (IISER Pune) each solicit the same amount (50 lakhs) to be spent on rack mounted compute nodes, which are to be added to an existing cluster (shared with 5 other groups) and provide the same justification (lab quota of compute time is almost all used up). The question arises as to whether this duplication is really needed. Another question that arises is the request for 57 lakhs to buy a MR compatible virtual reality goggle kit for the private institution (Star Imaging Research Centre) participating in the project. In projects that I am accustomed to evaluating and that involve government funding, acquisition of capital goods by a private partner is usually the responsibility of this partner. I just mention this point, because I do not know how this works in the case of ITRA.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B3. If any proposed major equipment is costing more than Rs. 2,50,000, and sharing/outsourcing is possible but not suggested in the proposal, then (i) do you know if that equipment is already available (particularly in India) where its sharing/outsourcing may be possible, and (ii) is it absolutely necessary for the project.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>I do not know enough to comment on this, although it is quite possible that other research centers in Pune may be able to share the kind of HPC equipment (compute nodes) that is solicited under capital expenses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C1. Any Additional Comments:</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>This is a compact project involving only four researchers from three different institutions. Of the four proposals I evaluated, it is the only one that proposes advances in basic science to drive the development of the promised deliverables. The researchers, though young and few in number, have good track records, and also work specifically in the area of AD and neurophysiological dynamics. My main reason for recommending support, for this proposal, which is closer to academic basic science than applied IT and resulting deliverables, is that such innovative basic research is also needed in order to really put Indian research institutions on the world stage in this area.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C2. Your Overall Evaluation:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=grammar\">(?)</a>(shown only to chairs)</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A.&nbsp;Recommended for Support</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#008000\"><strong>Reviewer 3&nbsp;:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A1. Problem (Item 4):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=overAllMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A2. Motivation and Objectives (Items 5, 6):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=reviewerQualification\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A3. Technical Overview (Item 7):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=potential\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A4. Activities and Roles (Items 8-10):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=fixability\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A5. Impact on Curricula (Item 11):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=novelty\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A6. Team (Items 12.1 and 12.2):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=technicalMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A7. Mentors (Item 13):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=interestToCommunity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A8. Outreach (Items 14, 16, 17):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=longevity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A9. Please provide your comments and suggestions for improvement on Items A1-A8 in 8 succeeding paragraphs, numbered paragraphs.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>1. There is clarity on the computational network part of the proposal but not on the functional MRI aspect.Using only non-invasive brain imaging to detect the proximate disruptive effects of theta oscillations (page 9 of the proposal) without localising the area of disruption (using techniques like EEG) may not yield much results. In other words, EEG should be used to identify and localise the anatomical region where disruption of theta oscillations occur. This information should be synchronised with fMRI data. Only then can location specific information is possible. Item no. 4 (page 9)- There seems to be no plan in the proposal for acquiring EEG data to localise theta oscillations for the fMRI studies. The inputs for network modelling is going to be taken from data repositories in pubmed. fMRI data are also available in public domain. For example, ADNI 1 &amp; 2 (ADNI - Alzheimer&#39;s Disease Neuroimaging Initiative) have fMRI data for AD patients. These can be used for the modelling rather than acquiring fMRI data from patients when information on theta oscillations are not going to be acquired from these patients. 2. Page 11 - The assumption that imaging data could provide deeper insight on AD progression is a fallacy. Imaging only provides structural information. Biochemical and molecular information would be required to understand the progression of the disease. 3. The section on fMRI data acquisition is not convincing. The team has no expertise in designing a paradigm for fMRI nor for carrying out the fMRI studies. 4. Dr. Ashish Atre (PIN 2A) does not seem to have experience in EEG or fMRI. Neither does his cv mention anything about his expertise in fMRI nor any information is available in the net. The role envisaged in the proposal for Dr. Atre does not match with his expertise. Page 34, Technical plan for fMRI studies - there seems to be no expertise in the team to carry out these studies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B1. Any major mismatches in the proposed line item costs with the proposed item/work, in the format: Budget-head-Institution: Remarks. Example: &lt;Manpower-IITX: Remarks&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>IISER, Pune Both the LIN PIs are from the same department in IISER, Pune. Yet, they are asking for separate budgets (Rs. 132.9 lakhs and 123.18 lakhs, each). The demand by each of the PI for Rs. 69 lakhs worth equipments (same equipments have been asked by both of them) and 2 PD fellows for each of them are not justifiable. Star Imaging (i) If Dr. Atre has expertise in fMRI, then the equipments he is asking for should be there in their centre. (ii)This Institute is a private Institute carrying out routine diagnostic imaging. fMRI is still a research protocol and not routine diagnostic. So, how will the Rs. 63 lakhs worth of equipments for fMRI be used after the study? (iii)Funding for equipments for private Institutions is generally not provided IISER, Bhopal There seems to be some discrepancy in the budget calculation It seems to be a hyped up budget</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B2. Any major equipment proposed for purchase that may be otherwise possible to share with others or is usable through outsourcing, without adversely affecting the work.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Computers with computational capabilities should be available with IISER, Pune group since they work in the area of computational modelling. They have also not mentioned the facilities available with them. This needs to be checked. Same with IISER, Bhopal as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B3. If any proposed major equipment is costing more than Rs. 2,50,000, and sharing/outsourcing is possible but not suggested in the proposal, then (i) do you know if that equipment is already available (particularly in India) where its sharing/outsourcing may be possible, and (ii) is it absolutely necessary for the project.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>same comments as in B2. Both the PIs from IISER, Pune have high budget ongoing projects (ref the respective cvs) in the area of computational modelling. The equipments they are asking for in this project should be available with them. They should be asked to declare. The same should be done with IISER, Bhopal as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C1. Any Additional Comments:</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Disruption in theta oscillations are not specific to AD. They have been found to vary in various other conditions like even during meditation. In AD also, there are reports of groups using resting state fMRI and/or EEG to decipher the pathway in memory networks. The proposal is looking at computation modelling for theta oscillations and fMRI as two independent and disconnected parts. It is important to measure the disruption in theta oscillations in the patients and use that data to analyse and interpret the fMRI data. This will have much more usefulness and impact. However, this is not what is proposed in the project. Since the team seems to have no expertise for fMRI work, that part should be removed. But the project will then be left with only computational work and no experimental data inputs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C2. Your Overall Evaluation:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=grammar\">(?)</a>(shown only to chairs)</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>B.&nbsp;Borderline</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#008000\"><strong>Reviewer 4&nbsp;:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A1. Problem (Item 4):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=overAllMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A2. Motivation and Objectives (Items 5, 6):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=reviewerQualification\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A3. Technical Overview (Item 7):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=potential\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A4. Activities and Roles (Items 8-10):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=fixability\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A5. Impact on Curricula (Item 11):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=novelty\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A6. Team (Items 12.1 and 12.2):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=technicalMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A7. Mentors (Item 13):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=interestToCommunity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A8. Outreach (Items 14, 16, 17):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=longevity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>B1. Any major mismatches in the proposed line item costs with the proposed item/work, in the format: Budget-head-Institution: Remarks. Example: &lt;Manpower-IITX: Remarks&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Use of noninvasive brain imaging to detect the effects of the disruption of theta oscillations and implications is memory are good ideas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B2. Any major equipment proposed for purchase that may be otherwise possible to share with others or is usable through outsourcing, without adversely affecting the work.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>-</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B3. If any proposed major equipment is costing more than Rs. 2,50,000, and sharing/outsourcing is possible but not suggested in the proposal, then (i) do you know if that equipment is already available (particularly in India) where its sharing/outsourcing may be possible, and (ii) is it absolutely necessary for the project.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>-</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C1. Any Additional Comments:</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>The simulated models are excellent.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C2. Your Overall Evaluation:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=grammar\">(?)</a>(shown only to chairs)</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>B.&nbsp;Borderline</p>\r\n\r\n<h4><span style=\"color:#008000\"><strong>Reviewer 5&nbsp;:</strong></span></h4>\r\n\r\n<p>A1. Problem (Item 4):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=overAllMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A2. Motivation and Objectives (Items 5, 6):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=reviewerQualification\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A3. Technical Overview (Item 7):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=potential\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>5.&nbsp;Excellent</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A4. Activities and Roles (Items 8-10):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=fixability\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>5.&nbsp;Excellent</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A5. Impact on Curricula (Item 11):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=novelty\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A6. Team (Items 12.1 and 12.2):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=technicalMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A7. Mentors (Item 13):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=interestToCommunity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>5.&nbsp;Excellent</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A8. Outreach (Items 14, 16, 17):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=longevity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A9. Please provide your comments and suggestions for improvement on Items A1-A8 in 8 succeeding paragraphs, numbered paragraphs.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>1. The problem being addressed is definitely of importance and will enhance our understanding of the mechanisms underlying AD. 2. a) Extract subsets of signaling pathways implicated in AD that also play a role in theta oscillations: The idea of extracting a common subset of genes/biomarkers implicated in AD is interesting but since the information extracted from pubmed will comprise studies across human populations of different nationalities, age and sex which means lack of a common genetic background. It is highly plausible that different pathways may be associated with the same diagnosis (AD in this case) and genotype X environment interaction will further complicate the situation. Therefore, I am not entirely sure how feasible and worthy will this effort be. b) Use noninvasive brain imaging to detect the effects of the disruption of theta oscillations:The authors propose that they will also develop routines to analyse fMRI data including data methods for graph theoretic measures. Is this an entirely novel approach? It is very likely that such systems are already in place. if not for AD for other diseases at least. If so, how will this add up to the existing methodologies? c) I am not sure if the available data is a strong enough evidence to hypothesize that there is a single common node leading to the disease which the authors aim to identify. Is there a reason to believe that it is unlikely for the existence of multiple nodes that can still lead to same progression and end points? d) Even if the authors identity that disrupted calcium signaling might be associated with AD or driving the network towards LTH, this will just inform us on the role of calcium signaling but not regarding the factors that might facilitate calcium signaling disruption which I feel is more relevant considering the objectives of the project. e) fMRI based tool to detect early signs of Alzheimer&rsquo;s based on disruption of spatial maps in the entorhinal cortex: This idea of finding markers for early identification of AD onset is based on the expectation that theta oscillations might precede the onset of AD. However, will this be a reliable measure if disrupted theta oscillations is in fact a consequence of AD. 3. The proposed approach is indeed a novel strategy but I have one concern regarding the impact of the results especially in facilitating the identification of drug targets as the authors claim. If the authors interest is to look at the network properties pertaining to the role of disrupted theta oscillations in AD, I am not sure how does it facilitate the identification of potential drug targets? Network level properties especially in a scenario like this might as well be an emergent property, and moreover tweaking multiple components of the network might lead to theta oscillation disruption. In light of this, I think expectation of objective 3 is a bit over ambitious. 4. The required software tools are relevant for the study. 7. The expertise of collaborators across disciplines will help meet the technical demands for the proposed project.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B1. Any major mismatches in the proposed line item costs with the proposed item/work, in the format: Budget-head-Institution: Remarks. Example: &lt;Manpower-IITX: Remarks&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Ashish Atre: Star Imaging and Research Center-recurring costs-lab and filed consumables: fMRI machine time cost has been mentioned as INR 15,000 per hour. If one of the investigators (radiologist) is a part of the study, I am not clear as to why the machine time costs cannot be paid by the investigator&#39;s (radiologist) institute. Travel expenses for the investigator from IISER Bhopal appears to be on the higher side especially for the domestic travel expenses proposed. Travel expenses for Mr. Collins Assissi includes expenses for international travel to attend conferences every year for three years which I feel is not justified.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C1. Any Additional Comments:</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>The proposal appears to be quite interesting and a bit ambitious as well. While I understand expenses on one of the American experts, I fail to understand how attending SFN meeting annually can be a part of the proposal. I feel the budget requirements are highly inflated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C2. Your Overall Evaluation:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=grammar\">(?)</a>(shown only to chairs)</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>A.&nbsp;Recommended for Support</p>\r\n', '', '1');
INSERT INTO `husmin_old_reviews` (`id`, `priject_title`, `reviewdata`, `by_whome`, `review_count`) VALUES
(19, 'project490', '<h4 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color:#008000\"><strong>Reviewer 1 :</strong></span></h4>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A1. Problem (Item 4):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=overAllMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A2. Motivation and Objectives (Items 5, 6):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=reviewerQualification\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A3. Technical Overview (Item 7):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=potential\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A4. Activities and Roles (Items 8-10):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=fixability\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A5. Impact on Curricula (Item 11):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=novelty\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A6. Team (Items 12.1 and 12.2):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=technicalMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A7. Mentors (Item 13):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=interestToCommunity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A8. Outreach (Items 14, 16, 17):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=longevity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A9. Please provide your comments and suggestions for improvement on Items A1-A8 in 8 succeeding paragraphs, numbered paragraphs.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">1. The problem is well described, and the authors have presented a good description of the overall intentions of the research. 2. The motivation and objectives are well defined, and clearly stated. The challenges are great, and the authors will do well to achieve even half of their goals, especially within the 1-3 year time frame. I am a bit concerned as to how the authors will handle the protocols and requirements associated with both the clinical and biomedical practices that would be attributed to the HVS. 3. The authors are proposing a system for implementing state-of-the-art software that will deal with fluid-structure interaction, as pertaining to CSF flow within elastic walls (veins and arteries). This is a difficult problem to deal with, especially on a biomedical aspect, let alone the more conventional engineering disciplines. The authors are a bit optimistic with regards to their time frames for successful completion and testing of a suitable CFD code. 4. The idea of a human simulator is ambitious, but certainly interesting. It is unclear to me as to how segmented regions (whatever they would be) would be reconstructed to provide input to the CFD model &ndash; one model fits all? 5. The HVS would certainly have an impact on curricula, even if running at a marginal level &ndash; over time the HVS would likely be improved, but this would likely not occur within such a short time frame (3 years). Note that verification and validation is mandatory in running and trusting the software &ndash; this is really not discussed in the proposal. 6. The team members appear to be well trained, and some are quite experienced &ndash; but really not in the relative areas pertinent to HVS simulation and processing. The gap between the medical profession and the engineering/science professions is considerable, and will require a person with great skill at interfacing these diverse processes. 7. The mentors in both the health care as well as the CFD computational areas are good. What I do not see is someone that would be helpful in data mining/management to deal with the data that will be generated from the HVS. The role of CFD and the FSI is only a fractional part of the overall project. 8. Outreach would indeed be good, even for lower successes with the HVS &ndash; the knowledge would be accumulative and permit improved and better systems to evolve &ndash; over time. The strength of the project really lies with the interactions and associations among the various faculty and students at the various institutions. Here the exchange of information and data would be good among all the researchers, with journal articles and presentations occurring routinely over the life of the project. 9. I have some trouble seeing exactly what sort of feedback mechanisms would be in place ensuring sufficient and adequate updates to the various researchers of the project. The fields are quite diverse, and the overlaps are critical areas. Likewise, how would the system and HVS be maintained, and who &ldquo;owns&rdquo; the project? QA for this project will need to be continuous &ndash; and will be difficult and cumbersome.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B1. Any major mismatches in the proposed line item costs with the proposed item/work, in the format: Budget-head-Institution: Remarks. Example: &lt;Manpower-IITX: Remarks&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">None</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B2. Any major equipment proposed for purchase that may be otherwise possible to share with others or is usable through outsourcing, without adversely affecting the work.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">None</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">C1. Any Additional Comments:</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">An ambitious project with a short time period - consideration of a longer time frame should be examined.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">C2. Your Overall Evaluation:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=grammar\">(?)</a>(shown only to chairs)</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B.&nbsp;Borderline</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color:#008000\"><strong>Reviewer 2&nbsp;:</strong></span></h4>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A1. Problem (Item 4):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=overAllMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">2.&nbsp;Poor</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A2. Motivation and Objectives (Items 5, 6):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=reviewerQualification\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">1.&nbsp;Rejection Quality</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A3. Technical Overview (Item 7):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=potential\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">2.&nbsp;Poor</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A4. Activities and Roles (Items 8-10):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=fixability\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A5. Impact on Curricula (Item 11):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=novelty\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">1.&nbsp;Rejection Quality</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A6. Team (Items 12.1 and 12.2):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=technicalMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A7. Mentors (Item 13):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=interestToCommunity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">2.&nbsp;Poor</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A8. Outreach (Items 14, 16, 17):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=longevity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">1.&nbsp;Rejection Quality</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A9. Please provide your comments and suggestions for improvement on Items A1-A8 in 8 succeeding paragraphs, numbered paragraphs.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A1 &quot;The amyloid protein which circulates in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) undergoes structural changes.&quot; This proposal starts with this executive summary : which is scientifically wrong. Amyloid beta peptide is an extracellular protein and not required to be in the CSF for any structural changes. The proven structural changes happen when it is in the extracellular domain. May research papers have clearly demonstrated that structural changes of amyloid beta peptide when it is in the extracellular domain. It may be noted that scientific research shown that a person with huge load of amyloid beta peptide (found during autopsy but they had excellent cognitive profile and were not Alzheimer or MCI patients. So have heaving amyloid plaque load does not mean having Alzheimer. This is a fundamental flaw in this proposal. A2. There is a serious gap of current scientific literature and strongly recommend to read those from Journal of Alzheimer disease, Neurology, Alzheimer and Dementia, current Alzheimer&#39;s research. There must have been a section what is going on in India and external places. I mean proper literature search. I see a big void and lack of knowledge of this present literature leads to make mistake. A3. Please note that by measuring the fluid dynamics of the CSF can not help any clinicians to diagnosis of AD disease. This proposal is clearly stating that AD can not be diagnosed easily and fluid dynamics will help. Please note that entire world is working on early diagnosis of AD which is Mild cognitive impairment or pre-MCI. At the time of MCI there is no change of flow dynamics and this approach will not work at all. In my own experience, I have seen that when a person having bipolar disorder or depression or dementia, the flow of CSF is basically the same. A8. Being involved directly with patients of different types (AD, Parkinson, MCI and healthy aged person, Depression, Bipolar) and closely monitoring them clinically and through advanced imaging research, I am quite positive that this approach by measuring the flow dynamics will not help the clinician. I would take their write up &quot;The change in the CSF flow causes it to exert more pressure on the ventricular walls which undergoes deformation. The flow pattern of CSF within the Human Ventricular System (HVS) is complicated due to its complex geometry&quot; Yes it is complicated and will not resolve at all in terms of sensitivity and specificity to make any identification even aged people with depression and AD. This approach will lead wrong diagnosis and I am quite afraid. Every person&#39;s life is important and it is not difficult to make diagnosis for AD. The challenge remain if we could do it much earlier stages and that is the research focus around the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B1. Any major mismatches in the proposed line item costs with the proposed item/work, in the format: Budget-head-Institution: Remarks. Example: &lt;Manpower-IITX: Remarks&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Total budget is 372 lakhs and it is inflated . The overall budget should be cut by 40%. The travel cost should be reduced by 60%.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B2. Any major equipment proposed for purchase that may be otherwise possible to share with others or is usable through outsourcing, without adversely affecting the work.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">I have no comment for this section.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B3. If any proposed major equipment is costing more than Rs. 2,50,000, and sharing/outsourcing is possible but not suggested in the proposal, then (i) do you know if that equipment is already available (particularly in India) where its sharing/outsourcing may be possible, and (ii) is it absolutely necessary for the project.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">no comment</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">C1. Any Additional Comments:</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Researchers from Three outstanding institutes came together and formalize on research proposal without any literature search. It is simply assumed that &quot; The amyloid protein which circulates in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) undergoes structural changes. This makes it more prone to interact and aggregate, binding to other amyloid protein and forming small oligomers.&quot; which is fundamentally wrong. Another serious flaw is that by measuring the flow dynamics in the AD patients we could make diagnosis which is far fetched.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">C2. Your Overall Evaluation:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=grammar\">(?)</a>(shown only to chairs)</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">C.&nbsp;Not Recommended for Support</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color:#008000\"><strong>Reviewer 3&nbsp;:</strong></span><br />\r\n&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A1. Problem (Item 4):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=overAllMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A2. Motivation and Objectives (Items 5, 6):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=reviewerQualification\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A3. Technical Overview (Item 7):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=potential\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A4. Activities and Roles (Items 8-10):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=fixability\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A5. Impact on Curricula (Item 11):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=novelty\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A6. Team (Items 12.1 and 12.2):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=technicalMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">5.&nbsp;Excellent</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A7. Mentors (Item 13):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=interestToCommunity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A8. Outreach (Items 14, 16, 17):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=longevity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">C2. Your Overall Evaluation:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=grammar\">(?)</a>(shown only to chairs)</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">C.&nbsp;Not Recommended for Support</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color:#008000\"><strong>Reviewer 4&nbsp;:</strong></span></h4>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A1. Problem (Item 4):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=overAllMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A2. Motivation and Objectives (Items 5, 6):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=reviewerQualification\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A3. Technical Overview (Item 7):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=potential\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A4. Activities and Roles (Items 8-10):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=fixability\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A5. Impact on Curricula (Item 11):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=novelty\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A6. Team (Items 12.1 and 12.2):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=technicalMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A7. Mentors (Item 13):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=interestToCommunity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">2.&nbsp;Poor</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A8. Outreach (Items 14, 16, 17):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=longevity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A9. Please provide your comments and suggestions for improvement on Items A1-A8 in 8 succeeding paragraphs, numbered paragraphs.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Item A1: Alzheimer disease poses a very serious problem in present days and any solution to this, even a hint towards the solution, has immense social effect. In that sense, selection of problem to work on is absolutely on right rack. The proposers have correctly identified that the manifestation of amyloidosis results in alteration in flow dynamics of CerebroSpinal Fluid (CSF). As a result more pressure is built on the ventricular walls leading to shrinkage of the brain matter. However, it is not mentioned how these phenomena would be revealed through direct MR measurements or MR imaging. Second, no idea is given what kind of processing/analysis tools would be necessary to handle such problems. For example, how normal abnormal flow of CSF would be detected. The proposal is little weak in this respect. Item A2: It is true that research in Alzheimer disease, especially in India, is in very preliminary stage. It would be of great help to the physicians if some IT based diagnosis platform be developed. As a first step, the objectives, in my opinion, should be defined more precisely. Here the authors planned more broadly than the depth. For example, it is claimed by the authors that strong correlation of the image features and CFD parameters with the clinical measures of patient data is yet to be established for precise diagnosis of dementia condition. However, here it is not mentioned which image features and which CFD parameters are expected to have strong correlation with which clinical measures. I agree that it is a difficult task with such a poor prior knowledge, where even scientifically collected patient data are not available. Authors may concentrate on a smaller set of objectives more thoroughly. Item A3: The proposed work is really a complex task and has many interdisciplinary modules. Integrating the output of every module in a single platform would be great. To achieve this, it needs very focused and intricate planning, which I feel is missing here. For example, fusion of measurements from MR and PET images is itself a problem. It is not clear how these information would supplement each other to generate biomarkers, fluid dynamics etc. I think it would be difficult to generate image biomarkers without clinical input (see overview diagram). Second, the statements like &lsquo;Use of machine learning methods in amyloidosis is essential as it helps to identify potential patients most likely to get AD.&rsquo; does not carry any meaning unless we have some hint about which method on what type of inputs etc. Finally, due to lack of details it is difficult to judge which part of the whole plan is novel or demands authors&rsquo; contribution. I do not see much overlap between the proposed work and past works of the authors. However, some past works of the authors (especially PI and Co-Pi from IIT-M and IIT-Kgp) are related to respective activities. Item A4: This part of the proposal is well written and is totally accessible except a few typos. For example, LIN1a or PIN2a (7th sub-item of item 8) does not exist in the proposal. I assume these should be LIN1 and PIN1a. From the detail description of the work load it seems LIN1 (IITM) takes major load (way above 50%) and PIN1c shares very little. Second, verification and Validation of Segmented Regions (of MR and PET image), i.e., Activity 4 of Objective 1 will be carried out at IITM, whereas suitable expertise is available at School of Medical Science &amp; Technology, IITKgp. There are few other such lacunas. From the best 5 publications of PIs and Co-PIs it appears they do not have enough working experience in image analysis which is the core part of the project. However, I think based on the expertise in allied topics they can develop required skilled quickly. Item A5: I don&rsquo;t foresee any immediate impact of the outcome of this project on the curricula of IT or medical science. But is this really expected? Yes, some PhD works may be formulated and completed. But 12 PhDs (page 20) is a little overestimate. Item A6: Given the proposing institutions I believe the required infrastructure and support environment are available there. Time Commitment by team members is more or less appropriate. About the preparedness of the team members please see the comments above (Item A5). Item A7: The name of the mentor being proposed here is a respectable person and expert in his field, which has little technical overlap with the current project. The proposers expect him to manage and coordinate. I do not quite understand this role as a mentor. So, no comment. Item A8: Standard outreach programmes like seminar, workshop, meetings and publications are planned. I do not understand why it is planned to publish only in open access journals. Second, some vocational training and interactive short-term schools may be arranged to train up UG and PG students.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B1. Any major mismatches in the proposed line item costs with the proposed item/work, in the format: Budget-head-Institution: Remarks. Example: &lt;Manpower-IITX: Remarks&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Item B1: According to Item 11 &hellip; R&amp;D activity to make an impact on curriculum (page 20) number of PhDs to be guided under this project is in total 12. But budget section: Number of JRF/PhD students: 1 (IITM, page 61), 1 (IITG, page 66), 1 (IITKgp, page 71) and 1 (BITS, Page 76) It is stated that JRF/PhD students would get Rs. 25,000/- (+ HRA) / per month for first two years &amp; Rs. 28,000/- (+ HRA) / per month. But in budget table, for each student it is budgeted Rs. 1.5 lakh for first two years and 2.0 lakh for third year (page 61). Same error is made by all institutes. So I think this budget is hurriedly made without much thought by copy-paste method. Another instance of (almost) copy-paste: all three IITs have asked Rs. 10 lakh as overhead. Usually &lsquo;overhead&rsquo; is charged by the institutes at some fixed rate (10%, 15%, etc.) on total budget. IITM budget is Rs. 172 lakh, whereas IITG and IITKgp budgets are Rs. 70 lakh and Rs. 68 lakh respectively.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B2. Any major equipment proposed for purchase that may be otherwise possible to share with others or is usable through outsourcing, without adversely affecting the work.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Item B2: In this three-year, all four institutes have put requirement for capital equipments in the third year. I am a bit confused: when would these be procured and when would these be put to use? Second, no description of equipments is given (not even names). The term &lsquo;equipment&rsquo; appears only in budget section. So no comments can be made on sharing, outsourcing or necessity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B3. If any proposed major equipment is costing more than Rs. 2,50,000, and sharing/outsourcing is possible but not suggested in the proposal, then (i) do you know if that equipment is already available (particularly in India) where its sharing/outsourcing may be possible, and (ii) is it absolutely necessary for the project.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Item B3: Same as comments made against Item B2.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">C2. Your Overall Evaluation:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=grammar\">(?)</a>(shown only to chairs)</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B.&nbsp;Borderline</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color:#008000\"><strong>Reviewer 5 :</strong></span></h4>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A1. Problem (Item 4):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=overAllMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A2. Motivation and Objectives (Items 5, 6):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=reviewerQualification\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">2.&nbsp;Poor</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A3. Technical Overview (Item 7):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=potential\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">2.&nbsp;Poor</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A4. Activities and Roles (Items 8-10):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=fixability\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3.&nbsp;Bordering Acceptable</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A5. Impact on Curricula (Item 11):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=novelty\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A6. Team (Items 12.1 and 12.2):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=technicalMerit\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A7. Mentors (Item 13):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=interestToCommunity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A8. Outreach (Items 14, 16, 17):&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=longevity\">(?)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">4.&nbsp;Good</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A9. Please provide your comments and suggestions for improvement on Items A1-A8 in 8 succeeding paragraphs, numbered paragraphs.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">1. Study of CSF flow dynamics using computational modeling will be interesting. However, the fact that is a study of the effect of disease rather than the cause should be kept in mind. So, the statement by the proposers that it will provide solution is far fetched. There is no team member with clinical background and knowledge of MR in this group. 2. No information on status of knowledge has been provided. Details of what exists in literature along with references are missing completely. Segmentation of ventricles is a post processing image analysis. Its validation against different MR pulse sequences is redundant. It is not clear what the proposers are planning to achieve by this.There are many reports on MRI segmentation of brain volume and structures. No references have been provided by the proposers. Items 5 and 6 - insufficient information and very poorly written. This points to the lack of a radiologist or MR physicist in their team. 3. Morphometry of brain using MRI is a very old topic. There are already imaging biomarkers which have been identified using MRI. So, it is not clear what new imaging biomarkers can be obtained using established and conventional MR images. CSF flow can be studied by phase contrast MR techniques. MR ventriculography is another apt technique for study of CSF flow. It is surprising that the proposers are not aware of these. They should be acquiring data with these MR techniques for studying the fluid dynamics of CSF. The Figure / flow chart shown on page 9 mentions clinical data inputs will be from IIT Kharagpur and BITS, Pilani. These are technical institutes. How will they provide clinical data?. Moreover, PIN3 is from BITS, Goa campus (page 7). So, who is the collaborator from BITS, Pilani?. Page 10 mentions &#39;Image acquisition protocols followed in the ongoing projects may be adopted in this current project&#39;. What do the proposers mean by this?. These are sections which should be written with clarity so the reviewers can understand what the objectives are and how they are going to be addressed in the project. It should not be confusing. The proposers seem to think MRI and DTI are different. DTI (Diffusion Tensor Imaging) is MRI obtained with specific sequence. That&#39;s all. 4. It is not clear who are PIN1a, PIN1b and PIN1c. Pages 6 and 7 mention only PIN1, PIN2 and PIN3. So, it is difficult to check whether the roles match with the expertise. Item 10 (Technical plan, Annexure 1) Activity 1 - from where will the MRI and PET images be obtained?.How will the patients be selected? What are the inclusion and exclusion criteria? What are the MR / PET acquisition parameters?. No information on any of these crucial points are provided.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B1. Any major mismatches in the proposed line item costs with the proposed item/work, in the format: Budget-head-Institution: Remarks. Example: &lt;Manpower-IITX: Remarks&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">IIT Madras No items mentioned and justification provided for any of the budget heads. For example, equipments worth 53 lakhs have been asked for. No information provided on what these equipments are and the justification for them. The PINS from other Institutes have also not provided the items required an the justification for the items. This includes equipments as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B2. Any major equipment proposed for purchase that may be otherwise possible to share with others or is usable through outsourcing, without adversely affecting the work.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">No information provided about the required equipments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">C1. Any Additional Comments:</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The idea is good but the plan for implementation is not. The team needs to have members with knowledge of MR and a clinician I would like to commend the investigators for the following: 1. not overshooting the page limit 2. concise and crisp writing 3. not attempting too many things but focusing on specific issues 4. neat formatting of the text. It made reading and reviewing easy 5. clarity 6. not over budgeting These said, there are lots of gaps in the information provided. Dr. Arul Prakash (LIN1) has not provided information on his ongoing projects. None of the investigators have provided information of overlap areas between their proposed study and their past / ongoing projects. The objective is good provided the MR data obtained is on CSF flow rather than on brain morphometry. They need to include a MR knowledgeable radiologist or MR physicist in their team. They need to specify where such MR studies can be carried out. CSF flow can be studied by phase contrast MR techniques. MR ventriculography is another apt technique for study of CSF flow. They should identify an MER centre where these studies can be carried out. The investigators are completely silent on wha information is possible from PET. If they incorporate these changes, this would be a good study to fund.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">C2. Your Overall Evaluation:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://203.129.234.86/husim/hotcrp/scorehelp.php?f=grammar\">(?)</a>(shown only to chairs)</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B.&nbsp;Borderline</p>\r\n', '', '1');
