(12, '14', 'NA', 'Final_ITRA _11 Sept-2016.pdf', 'Final_ITRA _11 Sept-2016.pdf', 'new_file', '1) Title has been changed as per the suggestions.\n2) Well defined hypothesis\n3) Objectives have been reframed and made specific. \n3) Objectives are coherent and complimentary.\n4) The proposed work will be completed in next 2 to 3 years.\n5) Simulation work has been revised as per recommendations\n6) Budget has been revised as per the suggestions.', '', 'Yes, the research problem is modified, as suggested by experts, and well defined and the objectives are reframed as per the timelines. Furthermore, as highlighted during our projectâ€™s presentation under the reviewers input, the human amylin portion has been totally omitted. Please refer section no 6 and 15 b (Technology Development Plan).', 'Yes. The investigators have mentioned in the text that the mechanisms of AD are not fully understood and the available drugs have side effects hence, in the current research proposal, we  would like to target both these limitations by developing a novel drug delivery system for already existing drugs in order to avoid their side effects and biopharmaceutical problems. There is also a need to develop newer agents like monoclonal antibodies (mAbs) targeting the amyloid. \r\nUnfortunately, there is no simulator available to predict /model the process dynamics associated with amyloid related diseases. Further, there is no integrative quantitative simulation model available for reaction kinetics and fluid dynamics of tissue accumulation and clearance of amyloids\r\nBased on the above mentioned unmet needs and reviewer suggestion, the objectives have been redesigned. \r\nThe present study will be undertaken towards:\r\n1) Development, standardization and evaluation of novel drug delivery systems using clinical drugs and developing innovative bio-therapeutic agent (mAbs) targeting AÎ² for novel delivery.\r\n2) Development of a pharmacokinetic-pharmacodynamic (PKPD), physiology based pharmacokinetics (PBPK) and absorption-distribution-metabolism-excretion (ADME) model based on generated preclinical data. \r\n3) Extrapolation of preclinical data to human translation.\r\n', 'Yes, as per the suggestions the objectives are streamlined and are coherent.\r\nFollowing are the revised objectives:\r\n1) Development, standardization and evaluation of novel drug delivery systems using clinical drugs and developing novel bio-therapeutic agent (mAbs) targeting AÎ².\r\n2) Development of a pharmacokinetic-pharmacodynamic (PKPD, physiology based pharmacokinetics (PBPK) and absorption-distribution-metabolism-excretion (ADME) model based on generated preclinical data. \r\n3) Extrapolation of preclinical data to human translation.\r\n', '1	Formulation and design of targeted drug delivery systems for existing drugs 	2 Years	\r\n\r\n2	Bioanalytical methods and Pharmacokinetic (Pk) studies of designed formulations in animal model	1.5 years	\r\n3	Development of novel monoclonal antibodies	2 years	\r\n4	PK/PD, PB/PK and ADME platform for clinically available therapeutic agents 	2 Years	\r\n5 	Model development for amyloid dynamic modification kinetics and Simulator Development 	3 Years	\r\n', 'Yes, explained through flow diagram in the proposal', 'Details metioned in under point number 4.\r\nApart from that, the Principal Investigator and group leader, Prof.R.N Saha and his team have developed various novel targeted formulation and various screening model systems using ICV- Streptozotocin induced AD, insulin resistance induced dementia, scopolamine induced dementia etc. have been well standardized in our research laboratory at BITS-Pilani, Rajasthan.\r\nThis research proposal, if approved, will provide us an opportunity to develop novel formulation of drugs at a price afforded by our population and we hope to succeed in this task as we will be working will nationwide expert collaborators of academics and industry. \r\nFurther we have also explained the various approaches that we would be taking up in our developmental strategy which would address those gap areas. \r\nOnce we are able to generate a specific mAb or a targeted delivery based drug against beta Amyloid aggregation, we could be certainly able to scale it up to deliver it at an affordable cost\r\nReferences:\r\n1.	Vasanthakumar S, Nazeer Ahamad, Saha RN (2014). Nanomedicine I: In vitro and in vivo evaluation of paclitaxel loaded poly-(Îµ-caprolactone), poly (dl-lactide-co-glycolide) and poly (dl-lactic acid) matrix nanoparticles in wistar rats. Eur J Drug Metab Pharmacokinet, DOI: 10.1007/s13318-014-0189-6 (IF=1.6)\r\n2.	Saha RN, Vasanthakumar S, Bende G, Snehalatha M. IndiaNanoparticulate drug delivery systems for cancer chemotherapy. Mol Membrane Biol, 27 (7), 1-5\r\n\r\n3.	Sharma S, Rajeev Taliyan (2016). Epigenetic modifications by inhibiting histone deacetylases reverse memory impairment in insulin resistance induced cognitive deficit in mice. Neuropharmacol. Accepted -In-Press (IF=5.11)\r\n4.	Sharma S, Taliyan R (2015) Transcriptional dysregulation in Huntingtonâ€™s 	disease: The role of histone deacetylases. Pharmacol Res 100:157-69 (IF=4.41). \r\n5.	Sharma S, Taliyan R, Singh S (2015) Beneficial effects of sodium butyrate in 6-OHDA induced neurotoxicity and behavioral abnormalities: Modulation of histone deacetylase activity. Behav Brain Res. 291:306-14 (IF=3.3).\r\n6.	Sharma S, Taliyan R (2015) Synergistic effects of GSK-3Î² and HDAC inhibitors in Intracerebroventricular Streptozotocin induced cognitive deficits in rats: J Naunyn-Schi Arch Pharmacol. 388(3):337-49 (IF=2.47).\r\n7.	Sharma S, Taliyan R (2014) Neuroprotective role of Indirubin-3â€™-monoxime, a  GSKÃŸ inhibitor in high fat diet induced cognitive impairment in mice. Biochem Biophys Res Commun.452(4):1009-15. (IF=2.30).\r\n\r\nMoreover the collaborator ', 'Yes, hypothesis and designed objectives are based on current research and literature available.', 'Following are the novel work which will be done in this project:\r\n1) Development of novel drug delivery systems to minimize associated sustemic side effects of on-label/off-label drugs.  \r\n2) Development of  bio-therapeutic agent (mAbs) targeting AÎ².\r\n3) Development of indigenous platform for Pharmacokinetics-Pharmacodynamics (PK/PD) and Absorption-Distribution-Metabolism-Excretion (ADME) processes of endogenous amyloid formation as well as enhancement of amyloid excretion/elimination from brain by on-label/off-label drugs.  \r\n\r\n\r\n'),
(13, '13', 'NA', 'Revised_Proposal_ipsm_id_12_457.pdf', 'Revised_Proposal_ipsm_id_12_457.pdf', 'new_file', 'Reviews: 457\n\n1)	Please comment on the 3 year project feasibility. \n\n\n\nReviewer 1: Okay: Need to give info whether such similar study is already in plans by the PIs\n\nReviewer 2: Feasible.\n\nReviewer 3: Feasible.\n\nReviewer 4: The project objectives are feasible in the tertiary care setup from which the PI comes from.\n\n\nAnswer: \nWe thank the reviewers for their encouraging reviews.\n\nThe proposed study â€œClinical informatics solution for human simulator of amyloid pathology in the etiology of type 2 diabetes and its complications (AmyloidDiabSim)â€ is a novel, innovative and unique study. The study is new and none of the PIs have any overlapping study conducted so far on this specialization. To the best of our knowledge, this is the first of kind of holistic study proposed in the country on amylin/amyloid pathology in the context of diabetes and its complications.\n	\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n2)	Has the research problem that will be addressed been clearly defined? \n\n\n\nReviewer 1: Okay\n\nReviewer 2: Yes.\n\nReviewer 3: The research problem is interesting and defined but needs to be refined.\n\nReviewer 4: Yes. The research problem has been adequately and clearly defined and discussed in the perspective of literature.\n\nAnswer: All research problems and primary objectives that will be addressed were now clearly defined and refined. \n3)	Are the individual objectives specific? \n\n\n\nReviewer 1: Yes\n\nReviewer 2: Yes.\n\nReviewer 3: The objectives were specified but certain improvements were needed.\n\nReviewer 4: Yes the individual objectives are well defined and specific.\n\nAnswer:\n\nWe thank the reviewers for the encouraging and constructive reviews.\n\nAs per the reviewersâ€™ advise,\n\nWe dropped the 2nd objective: A comprehensive F18 probe-specific PET imaging on multiple organs of amyloid pathology (pancreas and brain) â€“ as lots of standardizations need to be done before this objective can be implemented. Therefore, the following approach will be considered as a contingent plan:\nAs a secondary objective and considering the futuristic PET imaging applications on amyloid pathology in multiple organs, an exclusive brain-storming workshop (Workshop on â€œPET imaging of Amyloidosis: Beyond Brainâ€) will be organized to work out the feasibility of PET imaging in pancreas (and other organs) for amyloid depositions â€“ involving the international mentor Dr.Vinodh Narayan (Barrow Neurological Institute, USA) and several other organizations in the country including our Bio-imaging collaborator.', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'Yes.\r\nObjective 1: Investigating the (for the first-time in the country) biomarker role of systemic Amylin / islet amyloid polypeptide (IAPP) / amyloid Beta (AÎ²) along with insulin and glucagon in relation to varying degrees of glucose intolerance/insulin resistance/beta cell dysfunction, adiposity and cognitive dysfunction (both cross-sectional and prospective studies). In addition, investigating the role of Amylin/Amyloid and other biomarkers in relation to the natural history of diabetic nephropathy and diabetic retinopathy\r\nObjective 2: Transcriptomics and Proteomics studies to unravel the islet amylin poly peptide (IAPP)/amyloid pathology. \r\nObjective 3: To measure the extent of amyloid deposition burden in pancreas indirectly via development of retinal or ocular lens imaging techniques using orally administered curcumin as a tracer as it binds beta-amyloid protein with high affinity.\r\nObjective 4: Tri-hormonal algorithm development for new generation â€˜bionic pancreasâ€™ insulin pumps using amyloid simulator information\r\nObjective 5: Computational analysis at the interface of clinical information on amylin/IAPP/amyloid pathology in organs/tissue/cell and systemic levels; To build a hierarchical and multi stage input-output model in the context of amyloid pathology in the natural history of diabetes and its complications. Applying the concept of IT Future of Medicine (ITFoM), it is aimed to construct an â€˜AmyloidDiabSimâ€™ technology by integrating the patientsâ€™ data and biomechanisms across scales in the clinical context of diabetes and to turn this information into actual knowledge that helps us in taking medical and lifestyle decision.\r\n\r\n', 'Objective 1 & 2 will accomplished in 2 years\r\nObjective 3 & 4 will be accomplished 2 year 6 months\r\nObjective 5 will be accomplished during the last year', 'Yes', 'Objective 1 & 2 will accomplished in 2 years\r\nObjective 3 & 4 will be accomplished 2 year 6 months\r\nObjective 5 will be accomplished during the last year', 'Yes', 'Yes.\r\nObjective 1 has not been pursed so far in the country and is novel and clinically translational\r\nObjective 3 & 4 are novel in that they have translational applications\r\n'),
(14, '12', 'NA', 'Proposal-Project Code 467.pdf', 'Proposal-Project Code 467.pdf', 'new_file', 'The proposed system is expected to enhance and catapult efficiency of clinician remarkably, regarding the early-onset, diagnosis, prognosis and treatment of amyloid-related diseases or amyloidosis (the term amyloidosis refers to a group of diseases affecting a number of organs including brain, kidney, spleen, and liver, and having in common the deposition of amyloid proteins in those tissues and organs). Espousing the new knowledge and therapy on amyloidosis from health science and medical practice with state-of-the-art of the ICT technologies such as mobile cloud computing, and neuronal nanonetworks, the proposed system is capable of enhancing the current healthcare practice regarding the amyloidosis to a new dimension that is at par with ubiquitous healthcare. The clinicians would be able to use the system in their smart phones, making the healthcare practice pervasive, and affordable. By considering the reports of given minimal number of diagnostic tests and medical histories of a patient, the proposed system would enable the clinicians to predict the progression, onset, and prognosis of amyloid-related diseases, and eventually provide a holistic treatment for such diseases. The proposed proposal also aims to seek novel alternative approach to treat amyloidosis, by enabling synchronize neuronal nanonetworks with central nervous system. By investigating with this bold approach, new knowledge and theory will be generated towards development of new approach to treat the amyloidosis.\nThe steady rise in medical cost in diagnosis and treatment (especially for amyloid-related diseases such as Alzheimer disease (AD) requires a series of pricey neurological tests) has put tremendous financial burden to common people as well as whole society, prompting Government bodies search for cost-effective, affordable, and quality healthcare. On the other hand, incessant growth in Information Technology (IT) has changed significantly the business scenario and the human life. Through this project we address the problem of minimizing the costly diagnostic tests for amyloidosis, such as PET imaging, functional MRI (particularly in India, most of the regions, such sophisticated radiological diagnostic facility is either not available or not affordable) by providing clinicians mobile apps-based  smart detection and prediction system, which not only reduce the prerequisite of pricey medical tests but also provide a platform for new innovative treatment and prognosis of amyloidosis.', '', 'Yes. Please see the \"Review Response\" document enclosed along with the revised proposal.', 'Yes. Please see the \"Review Response\" document enclosed along with the revised proposal.', 'Yes. Please see the \"Review Response\" document enclosed along with the revised proposal.', 'Yes. Please see the \"Review Response\" document enclosed along with the revised proposal.', 'Yes. Please see the \"Review Response\" document enclosed along with the revised proposal.', 'Yes. Please see the \"Review Response\" document enclosed along with the revised proposal.', 'Yes. Please see the \"Review Response\" document enclosed along with the revised proposal.', 'Yes. Please see the \"Review Response\" document enclosed along with the revised proposal.'),
(23, '24', 'NA', '452-Amyloid-Model-full-proposal-budget-revised-4.pdf', '452-Amyloid-Model-full-proposal-budget-revised-4.pdf', 'new_file', 'Revisions made in response to the reviewersâ€™ comments\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nPlease find below our response to the reviewersâ€™ comments on both the original proposal and the revised proposal.\n\nA)	ORIGINAL PROPOSAL\n\nReviewer 1:\nThe comments of Reviewer 1 on the proposal were positive and he/she did not raise any concern.\n\nReviewer 2:\nReviewer 2 did not ask any question on the proposed work. However, he/she has raised a few concerns with the travel budget, which have been addressed in the revised proposal as follows. \n\nComment:\nA9. It is not clear how the international travel fits into the project progress.\n\nB1. International travel asked is extremely high.\n\nResponse: \nNumber of international travels has been reduced from 6 to 3 within the duration of the project. Such minimum number of international travels will be made to attend symposia/conferences in abroad in the 2nd and 3rd years of the project. We believe this will be an opportunity for the team members to present their work and also to interact with scientists working in relevant areas at the international level.\n\nComment:\nC1. The amount of money asked for the project execution is very high and most of scientists who are part of the project will devote 25% of time for the ITRA project progress.\n\nResponse: \nThe budget has been significantly reduced in the revised proposal. In particular we have removed one capital equipment (Fluorescence Microscope) and reduced the configurations of the HPC clusters proposed for IIT Kharagpur (LIN1) and IISER Kolkata (PIN1a). The justifications for the equipments have been described in detail in the revised proposal. We have also significantly reduced the budget estimates under â€˜Consumable Storeâ€™ and â€˜Travelâ€™. Note that most of the team members will devote 30-40% of their research times for the ITRA project.\n\nReviewer 3:\nThe concerns raised by the Reviewer 3 have been addressed in the revised proposal as follows.\n\nComment:\nA9. The proposal is ambitious for a 3 yr grant-in-aid. Further, there are no novel candidate molecules and no specific hypothesis is addressed. The folding/ misfolding of proteins requires experimental validation at all stages using sophisticated biochemical methods, a factor that has largely been ignored. Further, there already exist server based prediction methods, which the PIs need to compare their methodology with. The proposal is general and needs considerable revision with regards to the above.\n\nResponse: \nWe agree with the reviewer that the entire concept of the HuSim Project is an ambitious one. However, the objectives under the present proposal are well-defined and the PIs are well-known experts in their individual domains. Note that this has also been highlighted by one of the reviewers of the revised proposal. Besides, most of the activities under different objectives will be performed in parallel by respective teams with frequent sharing of ideas and inputs across the teams. We are confident that on receiving full support from ITRA, we would be able to achieve success under each of the objectives.\n	The specific candidate molecules that will be targeted under Objectives 2 and 3 are different variants of AÎ² peptides, such as AÎ²(1-40), AÎ²(1-42), AÎ²(25-35), AÎ²(17-42) in their wild and mutated forms. The candidate AÎ² mutants will include single point mutations at A21, E22 and D23, which are known to exhibit accelerated or reduced aggregation propensity. In addition, attempts will be made to identify new candidate peptide molecules under Objective 1 that on mutation at certain locations may lead to protein conformational disorders. Proposed activities on these candidate molecules have been discussed in different places in the revised proposal.\n	According to the â€˜Amyloid hypothesisâ€™ formation of fibrillar aggregates of amyloid beta (AÎ²) peptide  is responsible for the onset of the Alzheimerâ€™s disease (AD). However, higher neurotoxicity of the soluble oligomeric forms of AÎ² has been implicated recently. Our proposal specifically aims in resolving this issue and attempts will be made whether this hypothesis is validated or not using both in silico and in vitro studies (Objectives 1, 2 and 3). This has been discussed in the revised version under â€˜Main Proposalâ€™ (Items 4 and 5, pages 10-11). Besides, we propose to carry out in vivo studies to test the hypotheses of inhibitory dysfunction in AD associated hyper-excitability and excitatory inhibitory imbalance, through hippocampal and frontal cortical (involved in memory and cognition) slice electrophysiology and circuit mapping experiments at different stages of the disease in mouse models (Objective 4). These are discussed in the revised proposal under â€˜Executive Summaryâ€™ (page 4) and â€˜Detailed Technical Planâ€™ (Annexure 1, page 40).\n	We agree that the folding/ misfolding of proteins require experimental validation at using different methods. The experimental tools that will be used to validate the folding/unfolding and the structural changes of the peptides on amyloid formation have been discussed in the revised proposal under â€˜Detailed Technical Planâ€™ (Annexure 1, pages 37-38).\n	We agree that it is important to compare the prediction methodology developed and used under this project with the existing server-based prediction methods. In particular, the performance of our prediction model will be compared with the existing models (Refs. 13-18). We have incorporated this in the revised version under â€˜Main Proposalâ€™ (Item 5, page 12).\n\n\nB)	REVISED PROPOSAL\n\nReviewer 1:\nThe concerns raised by the Reviewer 1 have been addressed in the revised proposal as follows.\n\nComment:\n3) In the first objective, authors are not clear what they intend to do. They propose to come up with new in silico tools to screen candidate proteins associated with amyloid formation. However, it is not clear which proteins will be used for this study. Even if authors plan to use proteins from multiple sources, it remains unclear because they propose their study on a-beta peptide. The second and third objective do not associate at all.\n\nResponse: \nIt is true that the objectives of this proposal are primarily based on AÎ² peptide. The in silico tool EvoDesign has been successfully benchmarked for globular proteins. Under Objective 1, this tool will be modified for intrinsically disordered proteins (IDPs) in general and AÎ² peptide in particular based on inputs from experimental studies on conformational registrations and hydrogen bonding patterns in AÎ² fibrils. Once we have worked on the various modifications of the EvoDesign tool and force field, it will be applied on different variants of AÎ² in their wild and mutated forms. Further, the tool will be used to identify new hot-spots, if any, that on mutation may lead to either enhanced or reduced conformational disorders. Modifications have been made in the revised proposal under â€˜Detailed Technical Planâ€™ (Annexure 1, page 34) to discuss this issue.\n	We disagree with the reviewer on the comment that the second and third objectives do not associate. Under Objective 2, we propose to carry out atomistic simulations and in vitro biochemical studies to systematically explore the structure, dynamics and hydration characteristics of aggregated AÎ² peptides (wild type and mutants) of different variants. Under Objective 3, effects of external factors and additives (such as metal ions, surfactants, small molecules, etc) on such aggregates will be characterized using similar tools. The results obtained from Objective 3 will be compared and contrasted extensively with that obtained from Objective 2 for quantitative understanding of the effects of additives on acceleration/inhibition of aggregation behavior. This has already been mentioned in detail in the proposal under â€˜Detailed Technical Planâ€™ (Annexure 1, pages 37-38).\n\nComment:\n5) The different objectives proposed are not written very clearly. Objective and and 2 complement each other to a small extent, but the third objective (brain slice experiment) is not associated with a-beta aggregation at all.\n\nResponse: \nThis comment seems to be incomplete and we are not certain about the concern of the reviewer. We find that the first part of the comment contradicts the previous comment of the reviewer. The brain slice experiment as indicated by the reviewer does not come under Objective 3, but it comes under Objective 4. In this proposal we will carry out brain slice experiments in wild type control mice and transgenic AD affected mice caused by AÎ² fibrillation and relate their functions with behavior in mice models. Note that Objective 4 of the proposal will provide vital benchmarks and standards for the work proposed under the next objective (Objective 5). These have been discussed in detail in the revised proposal under â€˜Executive Summaryâ€™ (page 4) and â€˜Detailed Technical Planâ€™ (Annexure 1, pages 39-40).\n\nComment:\n8) Authors propose to study the effect of various additives on a-beta aggregation. If one searches literature, there are tons of studies on this subject.\n\nResponse: \nWe agree with the reviewer that significant experimental (in vitro) studies are reported in the literature on this topic. However, not much efforts have been made to obtain microscopic understanding of the problem from simulation/modeling studies. Besides, controversy often exists between modeling and experimental studies due to different conditions adopted in the two. The unique feature of this project (Objective 3) is that, here both in silico simulation/modeling and in vitro studies (biophysical experiments) will be performed on same candidate molecules under similar conditions. On one hand, molecular level inputs obtained  from the simulation studies will be used to design suitable experiments, while on the other the experimental data will be used to improve the models and interaction parameters in simulations. As a result, our studies has the potential to bridge the gap between modeling and experimental studies on the effects of additives on AÎ² aggregation. This has been discussed in the revised proposal under â€˜Detailed Technical Planâ€™ (Annexure 1, pages 37-38).\n\nComment:\n12) According to me, the project is not written very clearly and the novelty in using additives to follow abeta aggregation is less. Objectives 2 & 3 do not complement each other.\n\nResponse: \nWe have discussed this in our response to the earlier comments of the reviewer.\n\nReviewer 2:\nThe comments of Reviewer 2 on the proposal were positive and he/she did not raise any concern and recommended the project for support. \n\nReviewer 3:\nReviewer 3 has recommended the project for support subjected to minor revisions. The concerns raised by him/her have been addressed in the revised proposal as follows.\n\nComment:\n13) Observations The proposal has PIs who are conversant with their individual domains. The research problem, however, that will be addressed during the course of this project has not been well defined, as reflected by the title of the proposal. Further, whilst, the objectives and deliverables are clearly stated and achievable, the PIs have not elaborated on the mutations that they wish to study during the course of the project. The rationale for this selection, too, must be included in the revised proposal. A working biochemical hypothesis, is m\n\nResponse: \nThe PIs involved in this proposal are well-known experts in their own domains, and we thank the reviewer for rightly pointing that out. We believe that the research problem that will be addressed in this proposal has been well-defined with several interconnected objectives, which is appreciated by the reviewer. Note that in this, we will use a unique approach where a combination of in silico, in vitro, and in vivo studies have been envisaged to obtain a quantitative knowledge of amyloid proteins and their aggregations with a specific target to provide pre-clinical level understanding of AD in particular, and possibly for other neurodegenerative diseases as well.  The mutations that we primarily wish to study have been discussed in the revised proposal under â€˜Detailed Technical Planâ€™ (Annexure 1, pages 35-36).\n', '', 'Yes. The research problem that will be addressed has been clearly defined with several interconnected objectives and deliverables, which is also appreciated by the reviewers.  Note that in this proposal, we will use a unique approach where a combination of in silico, in vitro, and in vivo studies have been envisaged to obtain a quantitative knowledge of amyloid proteins and their aggregations with a specific target to provide pre-clinical level understanding of AD in particular, and possibly for other neurodegenerative diseases as well.', 'Yes. The objectives of the proposal are based around the â€˜Amyloid hypothesisâ€™. According to this hypothesis, formation of fibrillar aggregates of amyloid beta (AÎ²) peptide is responsible for the onset of the Alzheimerâ€™s disease (AD). However, recent findings that the soluble oligomeric forms of AÎ² are more neurotoxic than the insoluble amyloid plaques bring in controversy toward the validity of this hypothesis. Our proposal aims in resolving this issue and attempts will be made whether this hypothesis is validated or not using a combination of in silico, in vitro, and in vivo studies. First, formation of oligomers and fibrillar aggregates of AÎ² peptides and its variants (wild forms and mutants) and their characteristic features will be studied using modeling/simulations, and biophysical experiments. Following which, in vivo studies will be carried out to test the hypotheses of inhibitory dysfunction in AD associated hyper-excitability and excitatory inhibitory imbalance, through hippocampal and frontal cortical (involved in memory and cognition) slice electrophysiology and circuit mapping experiments at different stages of the disease in mouse models.', 'Yes. The proposal has 5 specific objectives which are interconnected and clearly stated. This has also been indicated by one of the reviewers.', 'The objectives of the proposal and the timelines of activities and deliverables under each of those are highlighted below.\r\n\r\nObjective 1: Development of computational tools to screen different variants of Aï¢ and other candidate proteins (wild type and mutants) associated with amyloid formation on the basis of their misfolding propensity\r\n\r\n	Activity 1: Development of computational tools to screen proteins (wild type and mutants) associated with amyloid formation on the basis of their misfolding propensity\r\n	Year 1:\r\n                   (a)	Customization of protein design software\r\n                   (b)	Benchmarking of the developed software\r\n\r\n        Year 2:\r\n                   (a)	Classification of proteins\r\n                   (b)	Analysis of results\r\n\r\n        Year 3:\r\n                  (a)	Feedback and fine tuning of the tool\r\n                  (b)	Communicating papers for publication\r\n\r\n	Activity 2: Identification of the hot-spot residues and the effect of mutation on the amyloid aggregation\r\n	Year 1:\r\n                   (a)	Development of algorithm for prediction of hot-spots\r\n                   (b)	Benchmarking of the software tool\r\n\r\n       Year 2:\r\n                  (a)	Characterization of hot-spots (inhibitors/enhancers)\r\n                  (b)	Analysis of the effect of mutation on the amyloid aggregate\r\n\r\n         Year 3:\r\n                   (a)	Feedback from the in vitro experimental method and fine tuning the algorithm\r\n                   (b)	Preparation of manuscripts for publication\r\n\r\nObjective 2: To explore the structure, dynamics, and hydration characteristics of amyloid peptides (wild type and mutants) and their misfolded aggregates\r\n\r\n          Activity 1: Conformational properties of amyloid peptide monomers and their hydration behaviour from MD simulations\r\n	  Year 1:\r\n                    (a) Generation of ensembles of AÎ²1-40, AÎ²1-42, AÎ²25-35, AÎ²17-42 monomer conformations; Simulation setups\r\n                    (b)Preliminary simulations; Testing of models\r\n\r\n        Year 2:\r\n                  (a)	Long MD simulations (microseconds) of different systems\r\n                  (b)	Analysis of the simulated data\r\n\r\n        Year 3:\r\n                   (a)	Analysis (contd); Comparison with experimental data\r\n                   (b)	Preparation of manuscript for publication\r\n\r\n	Activity 2: Aggregation behaviour of amyloid peptides and the role played by water in the aggregation process from MD simulations and biophysical experiments\r\n	Year 1:\r\n                   (a)	Generation of ensemble of amyloid aggregates of AÎ²1-40, AÎ²1-42, AÎ²25-35, AÎ²17-42 simulation setups\r\n                   (b)	Preliminary simulation and experimental studies on aggregation\r\n\r\n       Year 2:\r\n                  (a)	 Long MD simulations; Mutation experiments on aggregation kinetics\r\n\r\n	Year 3:\r\n                  (a)	 Analysis of simulated data and comparison with experimental results\r\n                  (b)	 Preparation of manuscripts for publication\r\n\r\nObjective 3: Effects of external factors and additives on the aggregation/fibrillation process of the amyloid peptides (wild type and mutants)\r\n\r\n         Activity 1: MD simulations of amyloid peptide aggregations under the influence of external additives\r\n	 Year 1:\r\n                   (a)	 Simulation setups with appropriate choice of external factors and additives\r\n                   (b)	Preliminary MD simulations; Testing of models\r\n\r\n        Year 2:\r\n                  (a)	Long MD simulations (microseconds) under different conditions\r\n                  (b)	Analysis of trajectories\r\n\r\n       Year 3:\r\n                  (a)	Analysis (contd); Comparison with experimental data\r\n                  (b)	Preparation of manuscript for publication\r\n\r\n	Activity 2: In vitro studies of the effects of external additives on the amyloid aggregation/fibrillation process using different biophysical techniques\r\n	Year 1:\r\n                   (a)	 Experimental setups with appropriate choice of external factors and additives; Preparation of fibrils and aggregated proteins\r\n                  (b)	 Preliminary characterization of fibrils and aggregated proteins\r\n\r\n       Year 2:\r\n                  (a)	 Investigation of the effect of the external factors by biophysical techniques\r\n\r\n       Year 3:\r\n                  (a)	 Effects to be checked on mouse models\r\n                  (b)	 Report/paper preparation\r\n\r\nObjective 4: Testing hyper-excitability and excitation inhibition imbalance in hippocampus and frontal cortex and behavioural deficits in mouse models\r\n\r\n        Activity 1: Brain slice experiments of hippocampus and frontal cortex to obtain precise changes in inhibitory circuits with AD onset\r\n	Year 1:\r\n                   (a)	 Wild type control, micro circuitry of PV+ and SOM+ INNs in HC\r\n\r\n       Year 2:\r\n                  (a)	 Same as above in AD mouse model\r\n\r\n      Year 3:\r\n                 (a)	Computational analysis of neuronal networks in normal and different stages in AD model\r\n                 (b)	Writing of manuscripts\r\n\r\n	Activity 2: Establishment of behavioural experiments on learning, memory and novel object recognition in mouse models\r\n	Year 1:\r\n                   (a)	 Wild type control behavioural experiments\r\n\r\n      Year 2:\r\n                 (a)	 Behavioural deficits in AD models\r\n\r\n     Year 3:\r\n                (a)	 Establishing links between behavioural deficits and HC / FC circuitry changes at different stages of AD\r\n                (b)	 Writing and possible causal experiments with optogenetic manipulation of circuit elements to rescue behavioural phenotypes\r\n\r\nObjective 5: Development of infusion based mouse models of AD (based on information obtained from Objectives 1-3) and test efficacy of external factors and additives in-vivo through behavioural analysis\r\n\r\n          Activity 1: Infusion based mouse models will be set up through injections in hippocampus and/or frontal cortex to test whether identified molecules in Objectives I-III produce observed deficits\r\n	  Year 1:\r\n                     (a) Start with existing infusion based model of AD and establishing the protocol\r\n\r\n          Year 2:\r\n                    (a) Based on Objective I-III develop new infusion based model\r\n                    (b) Test whether effects on (inhibitory) circuitry in such models mimic AD\r\n\r\n       Year 3:\r\n                  (a)	 Learning related behaviour analysis and deficits of Infusion based mouse models and plausible ways to overcome deficits\r\n                  (b)	Writing of manuscripts/reports\r\n\r\n	Activity 2: In vivo testing of external factors and additives on infusion based models (or transgenic mouse models of AD) from Objective III in overcoming circuit and behavioural phenotypes\r\n	Year 1:\r\n                   (a)	 Control experiments on mouse models to check dosage\r\n                   (b)	 In vivo testing of external factors on infusion based models/transgenic mice\r\n\r\n       Year 2:\r\n                  (a)	 In vivo testing of external factors on infusion based models/transgenic mice (contd)\r\n                  (b)	 Effect on behavioural and circuit level phenotypes\r\n\r\n        Year 3:\r\n                   (a)	 Effect on behavioural and circuit level phenotypes (contd.)\r\n                   (b)	Compilation of results; Report/paper presentation\r\n', 'Yes. The proposed work under different objectives has been coherent and they complement each other. As mentioned in the â€˜Executive Summaryâ€™ and under â€˜Detailed Technical Planâ€™ of the revised proposal, the research problem that will be addressed in this proposal has been well-defined with several interconnected objectives, which is also highlighted by the reviewers. Note that in this project, we will use a unique approach where a combination of in silico, in vitro, and in vivo studies have been envisaged to obtain a quantitative knowledge of amyloid proteins and their aggregations with a specific target to provide pre-clinical level understanding of AD in particular, and possibly for other neurodegenerative diseases as well.  ', 'It may be noted that the objectives under the present proposal are well-defined and the PIs are well-known experts in their individual domains. This has also been highlighted by the reviewers of the revised proposal. Besides, most of the activities under different objectives will be performed in parallel by respective teams with frequent sharing of ideas and inputs across the teams. We are confident that on receiving full support from ITRA, we would be able to achieve our goal under each of the objectives.', 'Yes. The review of literature for different objectives has been adequate and exhaustive.', 'Yes. There are several potentially novel outputs expected from this project, which include\r\n(i)	Establishment of a unique approach that combined in silico, in vitro, and in vivo studies to obtain a quantitative knowledge of amyloid proteins and their aggregations with a specific target to provide pre-clinical level understanding of AD in particular, and possibly for other neurodegenerative diseases as well.\r\n(ii)	Development of the web versions of the software tools developed which will be made available in public domain for demonstration and use by researchers and clinicians. These tools in the proposed simulator will be able to take different candidate proteins as inputs and provide their propensity to aggregate under different conditions as outputs. This can help initial screening of protein structures before proceeding to the clinical stage. \r\n(iii)	 Development of analyses software/packages to efficiently process the trajectories involving intrinsically disordered proteins (IDPs) as obtained from MD simulations.\r\n(iv)	 Besides, we will also develop a flowchart of novel biophysical techniques to probe the extent of aggregation/inhibition of amyloids. This will provide know-how for researchers and clinicians to carry out in vitro studies before proceeding to the clinical application stage.\r\n(v)	Building advanced infusion-based mouse models for AD.\r\n');
