(25, '18', 'NA', 'Parkinson426_Revised_ITRAgrant_Ashutosh.pdf', 'Parkinson426_Revised_ITRAgrant_Ashutosh.pdf', 'new_file', 'Dear Prof. Ahuja,\nWe would like to thank you and the reviewers for providing us opportunity to revise our\nproposal and improving it by addressing review’s comments and concerns. We are happy to\nprovide you a revised version of the proposal: No. 426 “Understanding molecular and\npathological basis of protein aggregation in PD”\nOur response to the reviewers’ comments is shown in blue in the following sections. The\nrequisite modifications have now been incorporated in the revised version of the proposal\nwherever it was appropriate. In this version we are submitting following files:\n1. Revised proposal\n2. Response to the review’s comment\n3. Budget for the proposal.\nWe are thankful to your ITRA team for all helps and hopeful for positive responses.', '', 'Response. This is not a super ambitious project. To build a complete human simulator all aspects of the PD should be studied. This project holds high relevance as it is contributing towards efficient detection of PD symptoms. Firstly, the experimental studies and the modeling objectives would work in a feedback loop. The initial part of the computer modeling would be mainly hypothesizing a kinetic model based on phenomenological understanding from existing literature. This could proceed simultaneously along with the experiments proposed. In fact, the models would also serve as a guideline for setting up additional experiments. Conversely, the experimental results would also help \'fine-tune\' the model. Most of the experimental input for the computational modelling would be in the form of rates and measurable quantities that we would derive out of kinetic experiments. Additionally, the experimental structural studies (say, NMR work from Ashutosh Kumar) would serve as a starting point for our structural dynamics studies including molecular dynamics simulations. These simulations would help us monitor the structural transitions at a very high resolution (atomistic). We therefore intend to use experiments for both the kinetic and structural understanding that would serve as reliable inputs for our modelling studies. In the methodology and objectives, the role of the modeling of biochemical kinetics (2a) will focus on experiments to actually build α-synuclein pathways, this will rely on both absolute values (IITB multiple teams) measured from experiments proposed by the collaborating investigators and in functional predictions (Amrita University) generated from mathematical models of data predicted from structural bioinformatics (IITB). Per say, consider this flowchart of work in progress study of α–synuclein pathway Fig. 1: Modeled α-synuclein pathway. Estimates of understanding α-synuclein aggregation are computed using ELISA, SDS-PAGE and other techniques. IITB has already proposed this as part of their objectives. The expertise of Samir Maji already combines mutation related properties of such estimates. Modeling team (Amrita University) will plugin data from assays into pathways shown in Fig 1 to better approximate translations. To show attributes of what is done in our modeling as of today, see Fig 2 connecting various mechanisms observed during neural dysfunctions such as axonal transport impediment, dopaminergic release etc. Fig. 2: Cartoon of α-synuclein pathway in neurological dysfunction - validating mechanisms to observations. To connect this to neurophysiological function, Amrita University and IITH, will require validating several observations such as structural conformation-related changes based on valid reconstructions of the protein changes (IITB). While IITH will look into spinal cord functions, Amrita University will focus on cerebellum-BG pathways. Today, several works are already in progress at the circuit level modeling of PD related neural models. Fig. 3: Circuit diagram for how cerebellum and Basal Ganglia connectivity determines neurological function. Connectivity ref. Bostan AC, Strick PL (2010). The cerebellum and basal ganglia are interconnected. Neuropsychol Rev 20:261–270. There is a significant preliminary work between in the CNS circuits with the proposers (Amrita, IITH). A new set of papers on local field potential (LFP) reconstructions are being submitted which will also add on the NEURON platform and is a collaborative work with Yale University’s NEURON team. Using LFP to validate population activity will add roles of constraining network models to disease/control data. Amrita team has also modeled fMRI BOLD activity and this will relate the developed models to clinical reconstructions correlating data recorded in hospital activities (KEM Hospital) to HuSim objectives (Amrita, IITH) in the proposal. This will also tie in IITM’s modeling (proposed as another project) with the PD work proposed by our team. IITM (with whom we may exchange data) has developed spiking models of Basal Ganglia (BG). Fig. 4: Ongoing work at AMRITA related to this proposal. Modeling cerebellum, thalamo-cortical and basal ganglia microcircuits for modeling diseased and control. Using spiking models and spindle activity we are already able to connect existing models for reconstructing clinically relevant EEG/fMRI signals allowing multiple interlocking levels from experiments to predictions. In future additional EEG data will be generated in IITB and fMRI from KEM will further improve theoretical models. IITH and IITB models will be incorporated to code disease-related stimuli/response modeling with spinal cord and cortical processing. IITH has an ongoing project in the modeling of spinal cord as part of which biophysically and anatomically realistic models of the spinal cord are being built at the single neuron/synapse level with both conductance-based and spiking models. Some unpublished shots from our ongoing spinal cord simulator work are reproduced in Figure 5. Preliminary work is also ongoing in mapping out the pathways from motor cortex -> spinal cord -> upper limb circuits. The proposed work under HuSim will integrate the spinal cord models with the motor cortex upstream and the upper limb skeletal muscles downstream. It has also been proposed as part of the Objective 2 to create visualizations for observing the external manifestations of circuit and cellular aberrations in the relative firing patterns of muscles and motor neurons. Thus cortex -> motor output connections indicated in figure 4 may be modeled. Fig 5: [Unpublished work] Screen shots from ongoing work at IITH on anatomically & biophysically realistic spinal cord simulators. Above pictures are visualizations of a few spinal cord segments and the Rexedlaminae on a segment. Small red/green dots (not visible due to image resolution) are the neurons. The backend simulation is performed using NEURON and output single neuron / LFP activity may be seamlessly integrated with the visualizations. PI from Amrita University has been working on biophysically detailed and spiking models of cerebellum and now is into large-scale models for predicting clinical correlates during function and diseased states (publication of these modeling circuit properties as journal manuscripts would initiate in mid-2017, if funded early). Amrita also has a preliminary independent version of a spiking BG circuit that could be enhanced with IITM collaboration interfacing both HuSim proposals. This project will integrate clinically relevant multiple circuit models (Amrita, IITH, IITB) allowing clinically valid reconstructions of control and disease conditions (KEM, IITB) with varying molecular mechanistic implications (IITB). To connect clinical measurements to neural firing, we have incorporated the design of a new network model of thalamus and cortical (TC) circuitry and the basal ganglia allowing cerebellum efferent and afferent pathways to understand disease progression. The TC network will also allow to connect spindle activity to EEG via mass models (also work at PIs lab), thereby allowing reconstructions of fMRI, EEG and local field potential activity correlates in multiple circuits. α-synuclein pathway can be correlated to thalamo-cortical, basal ganglia and cerebellar inputs. This project will enhance retranslation of molecular mechanisms to clinical correlates via this modeling process.', 'Rev 2. I do not understand why so many components are there. Some section must be just\nremoved. in objective 1 section 2 it is oligomerization is known in the literature and\nwhy to include this in the first place similarly the human study with PD should be\ndeleted.\nResponse. We thank the reviewer for the response. ITRA HuSim mandate is to create a\nplatform where data generated at a molecular, cellular and clinical level can be integrated. In\nour proposal, all the sections are relevant in order to create a platform where data generated at\nthese levels (molecular, cellular, animal models and clinical level) will be used for modeling.\nTo build a complete human simulator, all aspects of the PD should be studied from molecular\ndynamics to human physiology. Therefore, we have segregated our objectives in three\nsections and included PI with defined objectives and sub-objectives. In Objective 1, we have\nlisted sections where we expect to understand the structural/functional aspects of α-synuclein\nfibril/oligomers. Soluble oligomeric species that form during the early stages of the\naggregation process have been previously known to exhibit toxicity (1). These oligomers\nalong with fibrils can also be used as early biomarkers for detection of neurological disorder.\nAdditional advantage would be that we can simultaneously monitor the structural and\nmorphological transitions accompanying α-Syn amyloid formation. It is therefore, necessary\nto understand the oligomerization process as well.\nWe believe that human study also cannot be deleted since information from human subjects\nwill be utilized for development of disease model. We require information from behavioral\nlevel using human study since it will be crucial in generating human simulators.\nThe individual objectives by themselves form comprehensive and viable studies and, we\nbelieve, will contribute significantly to the currently expanding gamut of information on\nParkinson’s disease.', 'Reviewer 2: what objective it serves bringing all these stuff where most of things are known\nhow anyone can develop cognitive battery where it is there already.\nResponse. Thanks you for the criticism that provided us another chance to convince the\nreviewer.\nAs mentioned in the objective section of the project proposal one of the objectives of this\nproject is to create a model for diagnosis based upon longitudinal studies and generate\npredictive analytics for simulating progression of PD and decline of cognitive abilities based \nupon multi-modal evidences. To achieve this goal, neurocognitive underpinning of PD will\nbe investigated and further based on the data, a cognitive battery will be developed which can\nreliably assess cognitive decline as disease progresses. The follow of the data exchange and\nvalidation will be bidirectional. The idea behind cognitive battery is to provide objective,\ndynamic and reliable way to assess cognitive decline and intervention techniques for the\nscreening, treatment and prognosis.\nTo tap variability of cognitive decline, event related potential (ERP) will be employed which\nis considered to be independent from disabled motor output. It provides an objective\nelectrophysiological index of cognitive function in PD. ERP components N2 and P3 are\ndelayed in PD and the latency increases are more important in demented PD patients than\nnon-demented. These changes are considered to be due to slowing down of cognitive\nprocesses. However, long latency in P3 is attributed to focal cognitive deficits observed in\nPD (5). Non-demented patients show increased amplitude of event related potential\ncomponent P3.\nERP component of N1 is delayed in demented as well as non-demented patients with PD, and\nthis may due to deficits in the early information processing stages, possibly due to defective\nattentional mechanisms. The ERP results may be attributed to differential effects of\ndopaminergic treatment on cognitive functions in various stages of the disease. Therefore,\none of the objectives is to ascertain neuro-cognitive underpinning of PD. The second aim of\nthe project is to develop a cognitive battery to help during screening, diagnosis and\nprognosis. Cools R and D\'Esposito, 2011 (6) showed that cognitive functions vary depending\non the level of dopamine, over and under secretion of dopamine disrupts cognitive\nperformance. In the early stages of PD, the dopamine depletion is restricted to the dorsal\nstriatum, ventral striatum remains intact (7,8) resulting into specific pattern of cognitive\ndysfunction dependent on specific neuronal circuits. The objective of investigating\nneurocognitive underpinning of PD gels with first and second objectives of the project\nproposal.\nThere are no standard diagnostic tests for Parkinson’s disease. The diagnosis tools that\nare available are clinical diagnosis based on findings of a neurological exam and information\nprovided by the person with Parkinson’s disease. The available batteries such as CANTAB\nare quite expensive and not standardized to Indian population. Further, CANTAB is static\nmeasurement. It does not capture decline in cognitive function as disease progresses. Apart\nfrom these advantages, the main limitation of CANTAB is its price, which is quite high and\nalso not very much suitable for the multi-language and multi-culture country like India. Lowe\nand Rabbit in 1998 have evaluated test/re-test correlations and practice effects for CANTAB\nfrom large groups of healthy elderly and found many of the CANTAB measures have poor\ntest-retest reliability and modest practice effects. It also only measures motor screening task,\nreaction time, paired associate learning, spatial working memory, one touch stockings, and\npattern recognition. It does not tap comprehensive cognitive decline in PD patients. Similarly,\nthere are some other assessment tools of Parkinson such as “Unified Parkinson’s Disease\nRating Scale (UPDRS)”, “MMSE” and “Montreal Cognitive Assessment (MoCA)”. None of\nthem is comprehensive, dynamic and reliable to screen, diagnosis patients with PD. \nTherefore, it becomes imperative to develop a dynamic cognitive battery for Indian\npopulation, which will be cost-effective, culture and language compatible. In the objective\nproposed here will develop dynamic cognitive battery that will depend on the severity and\nprogression of Parkinson’s disease. Parkinson’s disease is not a unitary disease; it changes as\ntime passes. So, unified static cognitive battery won’t be sufficient to screen, diagnose and\nrehabilitate Parkinson’s disease patients. Dynamic battery is required to diagnose and\nrehabilitate Parkinson’s disease patients at different stages.', 'Reviewer 2: NO , This study need 10 years to complete. Where is the criteria of PD patients\nselection as PD has 5 stages. nothing is mentioned there. Why PD patients will have\ncognitive problem ? Are you dealing with PD with dementia and that is a different ball game.\nResponse. We have proposed the objectives after having ascertained the feasibility of\neach of them. We have a team with committed and sincere researchers (10 PIs and their\ngroups); therefore, we firmly believe that we will be able to achieve each of the objectives in\nthe timeframe that is being proposed.\nThe selection of the patients will be based on the clinical diagnosis, with a TRODAT scan\nand some cognitive test batteries and the same will be repeated at the end of the study (two\nyears later). The data will be shared with the collaborators for correlation and designing the\nmathematical/ computational model for early diagnosis of the disease.\nIn response to your second question, Parkinson’s disease (PD) is the second most common\nneurodegenerative disease after Alzheimer’s disease (AD). Cognitive impairment is a\ncommon non-motor symptom of Parkinson’s disease (PD), but the nature of cognitive\nchanges varies considerably between individuals. Cognitive impairment is evident from early\nstages of PD itself and a variety of cognitive functions are affected (6). Sometimes they are\nnot clinically obvious but can be detected by neurological batteries in the initial stages. For\nthe later stages the impairments are more obvious like dementia in some people (7). The\nrange of cognitive impairment varies from mild selective disturbances to global dementia (8).\nFurther, the cognitive clinical course and rate of decline in PD are variable. although Basal\nganglionic region has been implicated in motor activities; it is not essentially motoric in\nnature. Recent literature indicates the role of these sub-cortical areas in memory and learning.\nThus cognitive impairment is exhibited in the PD patients (9). Further, at the time of clinical\ndiagnosis for Parkinson’s disease (PD), a diagnosis which significantly relies on the\nidentification of classical motor symptoms; at least 50 % of nigrostriatal neurons have\nalready been lost. Thus, it is obvious for PD patients to have cognitive impairment. There\ncome the role of cognitive batteries that will serve as major tools for diagnosis and prognosis\nof the PD symptoms. Although the clinical diagnosis is the Gold standard for diagnosis of\nPD; the use of DAT-SPECT (TRODAT) shows some utility in the early diagnosis of PD and\ndifferentiation from other non-degenerative Parkinsonism disorders (i.e. essential tremor,\ndystonic tremor, drug-induced and in most cases of psychogenic parkinsonism), since it can\naccurately detect the presynaptic dopaminergic deficit. The test has been shown to have high\nsensitivity/specificity by multiple studies. DAT imaging may also have some prognostic\nvalue for disease progression (10). Further, the cognitive clinical course and rate of decline in\nPD are variable. As mentioned in the previous response as well, to tap variability of cognitive\ndecline, event related potential (ERP) will be employed which is considered to be \nindependent from disabled motor output. It provides an objective electrophysiological index\nof cognitive function in PD. ERP components N2 and P3 are delayed in PD and the latency\nincreases are more important in demented PD patients than non-demented. These changes are\nconsidered to be due to slowing down of cognitive processes. However, long latency in P3 is\nattributed to focal cognitive deficits observed in PD (2). Non-demented patients show\nincreased amplitude of event related potential component P3.\nERP component of N1 is delayed in demented as well as non-demented patients with PD, and\nthis may due to deficits in the early information processing stages, possibly due to defective\nattentional mechanisms. The ERP results may be attributed to differential effects of\ndopaminergic treatment on cognitive functions in various stages of the disease. Therefore,\none of the objectives is to ascertain neuro-cognitive underpinning of PD. The second aim of\nthe project is to develop a cognitive battery to help during screening, diagnosis and\nprognosis. Cools R and D\'Esposito, 2011 (3) showed that cognitive functions vary depending\non the level of dopamine, over and under secretion of dopamine disrupts cognitive\nperformance. In the early stages of PD, the dopamine depletion is restricted to the dorsal\nstriatum, ventral striatum remains intact (4,5) resulting into specific pattern of cognitive\ndysfunction dependent on specific neuronal circuits. The objective of investigating\nneurocognitive underpinning of PD gels with first and second objectives of the project\nproposal.\nReviewer 3: NO, Details of the approach and technical details of how a dynamic cognitive\nbattery will be developed should be provided for objective 3b. The feasibility of this\naccomplishing this in the proposed period is unclear.\nResponse. Parkinson’s disease is a progressive degenerative neurological disorder.\nParkinson’s disease takes quite some time to develop. It usually starts by affecting one side of\nthe body by resulting in slight tremors in one hand. As the disorder progresses, the trembling\nspread to other side of the body too and other symptoms such as muscle stiffness, slowing of\nmovement, and deterioration in balance and coordination may accompany. Some of those\nwith Parkinson\'s may eventually experience dementia too with progress of the disorder,\nresulting in loss of memory and other cognitive functions. Cognitive impairment is evident\nfrom early stages of PD itself and a variety of cognitive functions are affected, mostly,\nExecutive functions, visuospatial, abilities, memory, prospective memory, attention, speed of\nmental/ cognitive processing, and language.\nExecutive dysfunction is one of the earliest symptoms as cognitive impairment. Executive\ndysfunction is directly related to freezing of gait (FOG). The inability to execute a\nprogrammed complex motor act in response to an established plan of action is considered as\nthe underlying dysfunction. Visual impairment is present among patients with mild to\nmoderate level of PD (without dementia) and there is correlation with cognition (verbal\nmemory and executive functions), postural control and gait, and functional disability (11).\nMemory decline is common among Parkinson’s patients. However, not a single existing\ncognitive battery incorporated memory in a comprehensive manner especially prospective\nmemory, memory for action to be performed at later stipulated time and place. Attention\ndysfunction is a distinguishing feature among patients having PD with dementia or dementia\nwith Lewy bodies and this creates a lot of difficulty and fluctuations with performance.\nMental processing is slowed down with patients with PD. It is assumed that mild dementia or\ndepression could have caused reduced cognitive speed. Language related impairments are\nusually not included in the cognitive impairment profile of PD. However, it is known that\nverbal fluency gets affected. The verbal fluency issue may not necessarily be a primary\nlanguage dysfunction; it can also be included in the executive/frontal dysfunction cluster of \nsymptoms. Some incidences have been reported of impairments regarding semantic fluency\nrather than phonemic fluency.\nA dynamic cognitive battery will be developed depending on the severity and progression of\nParkinson’s disease. Parkinson’s disease is not a unitary disease; it progresses as time passes.\nSo, unified static cognitive battery won’t be sufficient to screen, diagnose and rehabilitate\nParkinson’s disease patients. Cognitive decline is not uniform throughout the progression of\nthe disease such as the nature of executive dysfunction does not remain same from stage 1 of\nPD to stage V. Similarly, each cognitive construct changes its nature and mechanism as\ndisease progresses. As we know motor movement changes and deteriorates as disease\nprogresses and there is correlation between executive function and freezing of gait. The\nbattery will also incorporate information from gait dysfunction. One of the objectives of the\nproject is to get the data as each stage of the disease and incorporate symptoms in the\ncognitive battery. We will also strive to make the battery not only dynamic but also the\nbattery will be able to predict nature of symptom in the stage depending on the symptoms of\nnext stage. The battery will be validated not only by behavioral data but also from data\nobtained from EEG and f MRI.', 'Reviewer 1: Objective 1 and 3 gel together. However, objective 2 which involves\ncomputationally modelling of the dorsal striatal neurons, substantia nigra pars compacta, and\nother relevant cerebellar and basal ganglia neurons using compartmental modelling.\ntechniques, their integration to form a functional network does not seem in tune with\nobjectives 1 and 3. the nigrostriatal pathway.\nResponse: The role of computational modelling is to enable us to make informed, heuristic\npredictions on the effects of α-Syn aggregation [Objective 1] on biochemical and electrical\nactivity in (i) the affected neurons and (ii) the neural circuits in which the neurons are\nembedded [Objective 2]. This is why we have stated in the proposal the following aim:\n“Modeling the role of dynamics of control loops affected by PD: Implications of cellular and\ncircuit functions with learning and plasticity”. The dynamics of the control loops in question\ncan often not be explored experimentally, as the variables that determine them are not\namenable to one-at-a-time experimental control. This in turn is because the variables are\ninterlinked to one another through highly non-linear feedforward and feedback pathways,\nrendering the isolation of any one of them unachievable using current experimental\ntechniques. The problem becomes tractable computationally as “control” experiments can be\ndone with greater precision, varying one variable at a time, before moving on to\ninvestigations of effects of varying multiple variables simultaneously. The implications for\nthe neural pathways involved in PD of specific perturbations caused by α-Syn aggregation\ncan then be teased out. The aforementioned perturbations can be wrought at the level of ion\nchannels, for instance, or of their regulators, resulting ultimately in altered spike firing\npatterns (in neurons of sub-thalamic nucleus (STN), substantia nigra pars compacta (SNc) or\ndorsal striatum, as we have mentioned in the proposal). Altered firing patterns will translate\ninto altered network function and network dynamics, which will again be amenable to\ndetailed investigation and analysis since the study is computational. Drawing upon\nknowledge of neural networks and cognitive function known to be affected in PD, predictions\ncan then be made as to the effects altered network dynamics will have on cognitive function\nin PD. Heuristic simulations can also help us home in on identifying those particular \nexperiments which will provide relatively greater insights into cognitive mechanisms, making\nthe study design more efficacious. This is Objective 3 of our proposal. In this manner,\nObjective 2 will aid in—and indeed be an integral part of—linking Objectives 1 and 3. We\ntrust that this satisfies the Reviewer’s query.\nReviewer 2: It is a mixed proposal and PIs did not sit together and also did not have any\nexperience of clinical work, otherwise this type of incoherence is not possible.\nResponse. ITRA proposals are supposedly to be on a big scale, involving studies from\nmolecular level, structural level, as well as in vivo animal models. Likewise, this project is a\nmulti-institutional project which aims to enhance the retranslation of molecular mechanisms\nto clinical correlates via modeling process. Clinical components of the project will be dealt\nby Dr. Sangeeta Rawat (Professor and Head of Department of Neurology Seth G.S. Medical\nCollege & K.E.M. Hospital) in conjunction with Dr. Mohit Bhatt, Head of Neurology at\nKokilaben Dhirubhai Ambani Hospital & Medical Research Institute. Both of them hold\nrequisite experience in clinical work and based on the systematic sharing of information and\nideas, the proposal has been put forward. All PIs had several rounds of discussion to develop\nthe outlined aims and research methodologies of the proposal. ', 'Reviewer 2: NO, It will take 10 years.\nResponse. Grants funded by ITRA are designed on a large scale involving multiple\ncollaborations. This project will be the foundation for diagnosing and understanding of PD\nrelated symptoms. This project involves the expertise and coordination of 10 PIs and ~ 50\nresearchers which will ensure the completion of this project within the given time limit. We\nhave tried our best to provide appropriate response to this question in the above-mentioned\nsection.\n Reviewer 3: Yes, the feasibility of objective 3B should be justified with details of\napproach\nResponse We have proposed the objectives after having ascertained the feasibility of\neach of them. We firmly believe that we will be able to achieve completion of each of\nthe objectives in the timeframe we have proposed. We explained this as well in our current\nresponse letter.\nRegarding objective 3b, a dynamic cognitive battery will be developed depending on the\nseverity and progression of Parkinson’s disease. Parkinson’s disease is not a unitary disease;\nit changes as time passes. Therefore, unified static cognitive battery won’t be sufficient to\nscreen, diagnose and rehabilitate Parkinson’s disease patients. Cognitive decline is not\nuniform throughout the progression of the disease such as the nature of executive dysfunction\ndoes not remain same from stage 1 of PD to stage V. Similarly each cognitive construct\nchanges its nature and mechanism as disease progresses. As we know motor movement\nchanges and deteriorates as disease progresses and there is correlation between executive\nfunction and freezing of gait. The battery will also incorporate information from gait\ndysfunction. One of the objectives of the project is to get the data as each stage of the disease\nand incorporate symptoms in the cognitive battery. We will also strive to make the battery\nnot only dynamic but also the battery will be able to predict nature of symptom in the stage\ndepending on the symptoms of next stage. The battery will be validated not only by \nbehavioral data but also from data from EEG and f MRI. The details have now been\nincorporated in the revised proposal as well.', 'Reviewer: NO, PI see my earlier comments.\nResponse. Thank you for your response. Based on the existing literature only, the research\nproblem is defined. We believe that our study has distinct objectives, which, when collated,\nwill aid significantly in comprehending various aspects of Parkinson disease.', 'Reviewer 2: No, Existing literature can explain this\nResponse. To best of our knowledge, the project is novel in every aspect and well\ncorroborated by literature survey. All the current treatments available for PD mostly give\nsymptomatic relief and there are no specific drugs that can cure this disease. A significant\nproblem is that by the time people get diagnosed with PD, most of the dopaminergic neurons\nare dead, which cannot be easily replaced/regenerated through drugs and/or stem cell\nreplacement therapy. Therefore, early detection and intervention of the disease is essential for\nbetter treatment of PD. Collectively, information ranging from molecular to behavioral level\nas an input will be aptly crucial in generating human simulator. We therefore believe that our\nproposal is highly novel as it will address significant and multidimensional problems\nassociated with PD occurrence and its diagnosis, which is first of its kind in the world as per\nour knowledge.'),
(26, '20', 'NA', 'IITD NBRC Mechanisms underlying AD, 25 Jan 2017.pdf', 'IITD NBRC Mechanisms underlying AD, 25 Jan 2017.pdf', 'new_file', 'Amyloid aggregation within brain tissue is a leading cause for neuronal damage that\nunderpins Alzheimer\'s disease (AD). Neurodegenerative diseases (NDDs) such as AD\nare typically characterized by a gradual and progressive loss of neuronal cells leading\nto cognitive disability, affecting millions of people worldwide. About 12% of total\ndeaths estimated globally is related directly or indirectly to NDDs. The number of\nindividuals affected is anticipated to grow as human life expectancy increases.\nResearch on the development of a therapy for AD has so far had some success in terms\nof treatment of symptoms. AD appears to have heterologous etiology and several drug\ntargets have been proposed that are believed to take part in AD pathogenesis. Hence,\na holistic approach that incorporates a range of methods starting with magnetic\nresonance imaging of AD patients, to the measurement of metabolic changes in cells\nand protein expression profiles offers new opportunities of early detection and\ntreatment. In particular, we highlight that such an approach can link the biological\nprocesses of homeostatic balance between excitatory and inhibitory forces affecting\nneurons at the cellular level, to cell death at the molecular level.\nWe propose to develop a model that describes the molecular and macroscopic\nmechanisms involved in maintaining the excitatory-inhibitory balance (homeostasis) in\nbrain information processing. The model will also incorporate the metabolic changes\nobservable through changes in neurotransmitter concentration distribution in\ndifferent areas of the brain with appropriately defined parameters. The bridging of\nneuronal activation to concentration variation of metabolites, will give us a novel\nplatform to understand mechanisms that ultimately cause cell death (apoptosis) during\nthe progression of diseases such as AD.\nThe scale of modeling covers the following ranges\n1. Simulations of large-scale brain networks to predict brain activity at rest.\n2. Metabolic model to determine the alterations in key energy pathways\n3. ODE model of the ER stress response pathways and its relation to neuronal\nmetabolism\n4. Boolean and graph-theoretic analyses of AD network, to identify critical proteins\nthat influence disease progression\nMost importantly, the model will employed to identify microscopic and macroscopic\nmarkers of homeostasis to be validated against clinical and laboratory experimental\ndata. Further, the graininess of models at each scale will differ and would have to be\nintegrated to seamlessly permit prediction of queries of a medical practitioner treating\nAD patients.\n\nGraphical abstract: The overlap of the red outline boxes highlight the candidate\nregimes to bridge multiple scales.', '', '1. Has the research problem that will be addressed in 3 years been clearly defined?\nReviewer 6 : NO\nWe have made extensive changes in the text in several section in red fonts to objectively\ndefine the research problem and our modus operandi. We changed the title to better define\nour research problem.\n', '2. Has the hypothesis, behind the proposed work been outlined? Reviewer 6 : NO\nThis proposal does not really have a “hypothesis”. What is being proposed is that a model\nwill be developed that will scale multiple scales and describe observations from the cellular\nmeasurements of metabolites to macroscopic imaging and clinical data. This is in tune with\nthe orginal directive given by ITRA team for the human simulator. It was expected that\ndifferent research groups would develop and validate diferent models and these would be\nintegrated into one grand model of the human body, the brain being one of the selected\norgans. The reference we can make to a hypothesis is that we expect the model to make\npredictions of the cellular conditions based on the imaging and clinical data. This was to be\nvalidated using a 100 patient data. \n4\nIn general we have made extensive changes to the textof the proposal and rewritten many\nparagraphs to address comments received from different reviewers. We hope that these\nchanges and graphical abstract for the statement of the problem will help clarify this.', '3) Are the objectives of the proposal specific and clearly stated? Reviewer 4 : NO.\nWe have now reworked the objectives and aims in several sections of the text starting from\nexecutive summary and throughout the proposeal. We have also created a graphical abstract\nof the proposal highlighting the key tools and analysis platforms.\n\n3) Are the objectives of the proposal specific and clearly stated? Reviewer 6 : NO\nWe have sharpened the Objectives to highlight the specific deliverables and hope the revised\nversion is clear.\n', '4) Please comment on the feasibility and timelines of deliverables of each objective. (Do\nnot include literature surveys, problem definition, workshops, conferences, collaborative\nefforts, etc, as deliverables) Reviewer 6 : NO\nIn spirit of solving a grand challenge our questions are broad. As per the mandate of ITRA\nwe wanted to have a broad vision with which we can accomplish a few deliverables within\nthe next 3 years and extend this into a self-sustaining research programs, such as a Center of\nExcellence. However, the deliverables in the next 3 years are now clearly laid out as well as a\ngraphical abstract is presented which ties the work independent researchers involved in this\nproject.\n', '5) Is the proposed work coherent? (Do the objectives of the proposed work complement\neach other?) Reviewer 6 : NO\nWe hope after addition of relevant details, and sharpening of objectives and problem\ndefinition a more coherent account of the proposed work is presented\n\n5) Is the proposed work coherent? (Do the objectives of the proposed work complement\neach other?) Reviewer 4 : NO.\nWe have made extensive changes in the text during the course of this revision. We hope the\nchanges in text and addition of a figure to highlight the multiple scales now make this revised\nproposal more coherent.', 'Please comment on the 3 year feasibility of the proposed work?\nReviewer 2 : YES , Overall project is feasible except certain parts of Objective 4 that\nincludes MD simulations that are too exploratory in nature. Exact nature of protein\nsystems to be studied will be the outcome of previous experiments and hence nothing can\nbe commented yet.\nWe agree there is an exploratory aspect to the MD simulations and not applicable across\nboard for all the proteins. We will be limiting the MD simulations to only those critical\nproteins identified through graph theoretic methods. We have some experience in designing\nspecific experiments to test outcomes resulting from complex interactions in biological\nnetworks. These experiments are designed at the boundary conditions arising from the\nextrapolation of outcomes. Under these conditions it is easy to validate a hypothesis (in this\ncase, for example a disease outcome and progression) by simple cell culture experiments (See\nSV Vasaikar, S Ghosh, P Narain, A Basu, J Gomes (2015) HSP70 mediates survival in\napoptotic cells—Boolean network prediction and experimental validation, Frontiers in\nCellular Neuroscience, 9: 319. doi:10.1093/comnet/CNU011.) \n\n6) Please comment on the 3 year feasibility of the proposed work? Reviewer 4 : NO.\nAs discussed in ITRA meeting held in 2016, we were asked to submit a research program,\nwhere 3-year end deliverables are objectively stated. However, one key instruction was to\nwork on a grand challenge that can go to a self-sustaining mode by getting funding from\nother bodies and involving multiple institutions. The modeling and experimental validation\nwork being carried out by other groups whose proposals were successful was to be shared\nthrough regular workshops. Since our last information, this had not changed.\nOur proposal we believe strongly embodies this important aspect and dares to go beyond\ndoing bench-to-bench investigations. We have a very strong team of researchers from \n3\npremier institutes of science and technology and not one individual is aiming to do all work,\nneither it is practically possible. We will simultaneously work on problems driven by\nindividual inquisition and merge that in a cohesive thesis as any “grand challenge” demands\nand as outlined with this revised proposal. ', '7) Is the review of literature, with respect to the research problem and objectives adequate?\nReviewer 1 : NO\nWe have made changes to the background and literature to address this point. We have added\na relatively recent study in citatioon looking at DMN and AD : Wu et al (2011) Altered\ndefault mode network connectivity in Alzheimer\'s disease--a resting functional MRI and\nBayesian network study. Human Brain Mapping.\nWe have particularly stressed on the lack of models that bridge scales within a unified\nintegrative framework in pg 8. As of now, no comprehensive model/framework exists that\ncan conceptually put the observations across multiple scales.\n“…This is most likely because the alteration in gene regulation in AD, protein\nsynthesis patterns and metabolic pathways associated with its progression, and\nthe resulting functional alterations of neuronal mechanisms caused by the\nchanges in molecular processes remain poorly understood. In a nutshell, it is not\nclear how aberrant homeostatic processes are linked to apoptotic mechanisms of\ncell death during the course of AD progression.”\n\n7) Is the review of literature, with respect to the research problem and objectives adequate?\nReviewer 6 : NO\nWe have added a study citing alterations of DMN in AD patients and background work on\ncell culture.\n', '8) Does the project have any novelty? (corroborated by literature survey) Reviewer 1 : YES\n, it does but not totally.\nWe agree that some of the elements are not entirely new. However, integrating varied\nmethods for application across wide spatial and temporal scales is extremely challenging and\nhas not been done before. We hope our response to earlier point will highlight the possible\nnovel outcomes of this study. We have also tried to highlight the novelty across text starting\nfrom Executive Summary section the novel aspects of this proposal in linking the\nhomeostatic neuronal mechanisms to molecular mechanisms of cell death. We also bring out\nthis “linking of scale aspect” in a graphical abstract.\n8) Does the project have any novelty? (corroborated by literature survey) Reviewer 4 : NO\nWe hope the novel aspects are clear in this revised proposal that we aim to develop a model\nthat scales from the cellular to macroscopic mechanisms involved in maintaining the\nexcitatory-inhibitory balance (homeostasis) in brain information processing. We have\nprovided a graphical abstract to illustrate this.\n');
